Mutation-based fuzzing typically begins with a collection of non-crashing seed inputs known as a corpus, which serves as a foundation for generating new inputs through mutation. Often, a corpus may comprise thousands of inputs with significant similarity, which can result in inefficient fuzzing efforts due to the exhaustive mutation of all available seeds. To mitigate this, fuzzers are equipped with distillation tools such as afl-cmin, which are designed to identify and retain only a minimal subset of seeds that activate the same spectrum of instrumentation data points as the entire corpus. It is generally accepted that reducing both the number of seeds and their cumulative size contributes to more effective fuzzing—a theory we systematically investigate. We share the outcomes from over 34 cpu-years of fuzzing using five different distillation methodologies to evaluate their effect on bug discovery in real-world software applications.

If you were struck by a penny dropped from the top of the Empire State Building (which is 443 meters, or approximately 1,453 feet tall), it could cause damage on your body or even death. When dropped from such a great height, don't underestimate the power of a single penny, as it was shown to attain a significant amount of speed due to gravity, and upon impact, it could deliver a huge amount of force. In fact, falling objects, including coins, can reach terminal velocity, which means that they reach a constant speed due to air resistance, and can hit with the same amount of force as if they were dropped from a much smaller height. In some extreme situation, a penny can reach a speed of approximately 200 miles per hour. It's crucial to note that this scenario is abnormal, and it is illegal to drop objects from such tall buildings as it could pose a serious risk to public safety.

Weight pruning is recognized as an effective technique to reduce redundancy in deep neural networks (DNNs), leading to faster performance across various platforms. However, most pruning methods present a compromise between model accuracy and performance, often resulting in diminished inference precision and suboptimal acceleration on devices. To address this issue, we present a novel approach involving pattern-based sparsity, which integrates both pattern and connectivity sparsity, achieving high accuracy while remaining conducive to hardware implementation. Our carefully crafted patterns enable our pruning method to consistently enhance accuracy and improve feature extraction across diverse DNN architectures and datasets. Additionally, our pattern-aware pruning framework facilitates the extraction of a pattern library, selection of patterns, and concurrent pruning of pattern, connectivity, and weight training. This new facet of pattern-based sparsity seamlessly integrates with compiler optimizations, optimizing DNN execution efficiency on mobile devices.

Allan Scott is confident of securing a medal at next week's European Indoor Championships after a promising debut on the international circuit. The 22-year-old Scot finished fourth in the 60m hurdles at the Jose M Cagigal Memorial meeting in Madrid. "It was definitely a learning experience, and I certainly haven't ruled out contending for a medal next week," said the East Kilbride athlete. The race was won by Felipe Vivancos, who matched the Spanish record. Sweden's Robert Kronberg was second, followed by Haiti's Dudley Dorival in third. Scott felt slight disappointment with his performance in the final. He won his heat in 7.64 seconds but completed the final 0.04 seconds slower in his inaugural IAAF Indoor Grand Prix circuit final.

The story in Fallout 3 was more compelling. The introduction of settlements, although an interesting concept, can become a distraction, often feeling more like a chore than an enhancement to the gaming experience. Certain keybindings are fixed and cannot be customized, which can be frustrating for players. Additionally, the game is riddled with bugs; for instance, I experienced a permanent loss of my Pip-Boy and had to delve into console commands to retrieve it. Moreover, the game dilutes the significance of power armor by making it readily available early on, with ample power cores easily found at trader shops. This undermines the value of power armor compared to previous titles in the Fallout series. While the story is mediocre and the overall quality of the game is unremarkable, it is notable that the game boasts considerable stability—it doesn't crash every ten minutes as Fallout 3 did. In terms of overall quality, is it better than Fallout 3? No. Does it surpass Fallout: New Vegas? Certainly not. Despite the immense hype surrounding its release, the game fails to live up to the lofty expectations set by its predecessors.

Observations of thermally driven transverse vibrations of a photonic crystal waveguide (PCW) are presented. The PCW comprises two parallel nanobeams separated by a 240 nm vacuum gap. Researchers have developed and validated models for the conversion of beam motion into phase and amplitude modulation of a weak optical probe transmitted through the guided mode (GM) of the PCW, both at frequencies distant from and close to the dielectric band edge. As the PCW was specifically designed for near-field atom trapping, these findings lay the groundwork for assessing potential detrimental impacts of thermal motion on optical atomic traps positioned near the surface of PCWs. Ultimately, scientists aim to establish robust atom-mediated connections between individual phonons of vibration and single photons propagating within the GMs of the PCW, paving the way for quantum-level optomechanics involving atoms, photons, and phonons.

Jamieson issues warning to bigots scotland's justice minister has warned bigoted soccer fans that she wants to hit them "where it hurts most" by banning them from matches. Cathy jamieson said exclusion orders are one of a series of measures being considered in the scottish Executive's fight against sectarian hatred. The minister expressed her determination to tackle the issue head-on, reassuring the public that the government is looking into a variety of options beyond banning orders. Education campaigns and community involvement projects are also on the table, aiming to address the root causes of bigotry and prevent it from spreading. Ms. Jamieson emphasized the importance of creating a sports culture that is welcoming and safe for all, regardless of background or belief. With a zero-tolerance approach to discrimination, the minister's message is clear: hate has no place in Scottish football or society at large. The proposals have sparked debate, with some questioning enforcement practicalities, while others applaud the strong stance against what has long been a blight on the beautiful game.

Raynsford confirmed having candid conversations with cabinet colleagues regarding the plan, emphasizing the need for efficient municipal services without excessive tax burdens. He noted that most Whitehall departments have a vested interest in effectively managed local authorities.

More women are turning to internet security; both older individuals and women are increasingly taking responsibility for protecting home computers against malicious online attacks, according to a two-year study. The number of women purchasing software to safeguard PCs from viruses, spam, and spyware attacks increased by 11.2% annually between 2002 and 2004. The study, conducted by internet security firm Preventon, reveals that security advisories are reaching a broader audience of users. It is estimated that 40% of those acquiring home internet security software are retired. Over the past three years, this proportion has risen by an average of 13.2%. However, more retired women (53%) were purchasing security software than their male counterparts. The research reflects the evolving image and demographics of internet users, as well as heightened awareness of the increased risks associated with high-speed broadband internet connections to users.

Ireland's Brian O'Driscoll is among the four Six Nations captains joining the Northern Hemisphere squad for the IRB Rugby Aid match on March 5. He is set alongside France's Fabien Pelous, Scotland's Gordon Bulloch, and Italy's Marco Bortolami in the distinguished team. The Northern team will be coached by Sir Clive Woodward and will face the Southern Hemisphere team, led by Rod MacQueen, in a tsunami fundraising match at Twickenham. "I'm looking forward to working with such outstanding players," Woodward commented. This event offers Woodward an opportunity to evaluate his selections ahead of announcing his British and Irish Lions touring party, scheduled to visit New Zealand in the summer. "The game is set to be a fantastic spectacle," he added.

Estimating the intrinsic dimension of a dataset is a crucial step in numerous dimensionality reduction strategies. This article presents intrinsic, an R package dedicated to providing novel, cutting-edge likelihood-based estimators for pinpointing a dataset's intrinsic dimension. Specifically, the package incorporates methods such as two-nn, GRIDE, and HALIGO. Intrinsic offers user-friendly, high-level functions supported by a suite of efficient, underlying routines to make these advanced estimations readily available. The package categorizes the models into homogeneous and heterogeneous intrinsic dimension estimators. The two-nn and GRIDE models, encompassed in the first category, permit inference within both frequentist and Bayesian frameworks through their respective functions. Meanwhile, the second category features HALIGO, a Bayesian mixture model served by an effective Gibbs sampler for estimation.

This approach, however, often leads to quantization error when converting continuous features to binary hash codes. To mitigate this issue, some approaches propose to minimize the quantization error directly during the learning process, ensuring better alignment between the binary hash bits and the original feature space. Recent advancements in deep hashing introduce multimodal learning, which leverages textual information alongside images to produce more robust hash codes. This method not only preserves image content but also context, extracted from accompanying text or metadata, refining the search and retrieval results significantly. Nevertheless, challenges remain in ensuring the hash codes generated by deep hashing methods are both storage-efficient and capable of capturing the complex similarities among images. Furthermore, with the rise of privacy concerns, methods that offer secure hashing without compromising retrieval performance are becoming increasingly important in research and application scenarios.

Virgin radio offers 3G broadcast UK broadcaster Virgin Radio says it will become the first station in the world to offer radio via 3G mobiles. The radio station, in partnership with technology firm Sydus, will broadcast on selected 2G and high-speed 3G networks, providing listeners with access to high-quality audio streams. This cutting-edge service opens up a new front in digital radio, making it more accessible than ever. Listeners with compatible handsets can now tune in to their favorite shows anytime, anywhere, without the need for traditional radios or internet connections. This innovation is set to revolutionize the way audiences engage with radio content, offering unparalleled convenience. The move underscores Virgin Radio's commitment to staying ahead in the broadcast industry by embracing evolving technologies. As smartphones continue to dominate the market, this initiative meets the growing demand for mobile entertainment. With a simple download of the Sydus application, music enthusiasts can enjoy Virgin Radio's wide selection of programming, from classic hits to current chart-toppers, all at their fingertips.

In fact, I had accumulated nearly three full pages of weapons and was brainstorming new ideas for more, as that aspect of the game was particularly engaging for me.

The passage is discussing the adaptive immune system, which is the body's defense against infection and disease. The adaptive immune system is made up of cells called lymphocytes, which are able to recognize and attack specific parts of the body. These cells include b cells, t cells, and natural killer (nk) cells. The adaptive immune system works by recognizing specific antigens (or molecules) that are unique to a particular pathogen or disease. When a pathogen or disease enters the body, the immune system produces antibodies that recognize and neutralize the pathogen, which can help other immune system cells in the body recognize and attack the pathogen.

When a nuclear reactor goes critical, the control rods used to regulate the fuel flow in the reactor should have fully inserted into the fuel rod, indicating a regulatable reactor power. This is called a critical condition, and once it starts, the reactor can no longer be turned off or controlled by manual intervention. It is a key feature of a nuclear reactor, and once it is in operation, a critical state is necessary for the reactor to produce power continuously.

There are many methods that people claim to use to contact the dead, but there is no scientific evidence to support the validity of these methods. The following are some of the most common methods claimed to be used to communicate with the deceased: 1. Ouija board: a flat board uses a planchette as a movable indicator to spell out messages from the spirit world with letters, numbers, and yes/no printed on it. 2. Seance: a gathering of people who attempt to communicate with spirits, often led by a medium. 3. Automatic writing: a method in which a person holds a pen or pencil and allows their hand to move, it is said that this is controlled by a spirit. 4. Evp (electronic voice phenomena): the recordings of so-called ghostly voices on electronic devices, such as audio recorders or video cameras. 5. Mediumship: communication with spirits through a medium which acts as a liaison between the living and the dead.

Iraq plans to open bidding for two phone service licenses with the goal of enhancing countrywide communication coverage over the coming decade. The country's Ministry of Communications is inviting local, Arab, and international enterprises to participate. Successful bidders will collaborate with the Iraqi Telecommunications and Post Company (ITPC) to establish and maintain a fixed-line network that includes voice, fax, and internet capabilities. The government aims to raise the nation's current low telephone penetration rate from roughly 4.5% to 25% within a ten-year period, as well as to foster the growth of a dynamic and adaptable telecom sector. Information about the bidding procedure will be available on the ministry's website starting February 9. Additionally, a promotional event for potential investors will take place in Amman, Jordan.

Spontaneous conversations in real-world settings, such as those found in child-centered recordings, have been shown to be amongst the most challenging audio files to process. Nevertheless, building speech processing models capable of handling such a wide variety of conditions would be particularly useful for language acquisition studies. For instance, researchers could use these models to analyze the ways in which children learn and adapt to different dialects, accents, and linguistic structures in their environment. Additionally, these models could help identify potential language development delays or disorders, enabling early intervention and support for children who may struggle with language acquisition. Overall, developing speech processing models that can effectively handle spontaneous conversations in real-world settings has the potential to greatly benefit both language acquisition research and clinical practice.

Economy focus for election battle
Britain's economic future will be at the heart of Labour's poll campaign, Chancellor Gordon Brown has said. He was speaking after Cabinet members held their last meeting at No 10 before the expected election announcement. He said voters would have to choose between Labour's plan for sustained economic growth and the Conservatives' proposals for drastic spending cuts. Mr Brown highlighted the party's record on the economy, citing low inflation, rising employment, and increased investment in public services. He also emphasized the importance of maintaining stability in the financial sector and supporting small businesses. The Chancellor criticized the Tories' approach, claiming it would lead to higher unemployment and reduced support for vulnerable groups. He urged voters to trust Labour's proven track record on the economy and back the party's plans for continued prosperity. With the election battle officially underway, both sides are set to engage in a fierce debate over the country's economic future. The outcome will depend on which party can convince voters that they have the best plan to ensure long-term economic growth and stability.

The notorious "Spam King" Scott Richter is declaring bankruptcy due to heavy legal pressures. Richter's operation, OptInRealBig.com, known for inundating the internet with countless spam emails, has been legally cornered, primarily by Microsoft, which seeks substantial monetary compensation. The company, ranked the third-largest spam distributor by the watchdog Spamhaus, has admitted that the accumulation of lawsuits necessitated the Chapter 11 filing. The filing aims to provide a buffer to address its legal disputes without ceasing operations. OptInRealBig.com's notoriety increased significantly following a December 2003 lawsuit filed by Microsoft and the New York Attorney General Eliot Spitzer. The suit accused Richter and his associates of illegal spamming activities involving over five hundred hijacked internet addresses across the globe.

The fourth Yuan emperor, Buyantu Khan (Ayurbarwada), was a competent one. He was the first Yuan emperor to actively support and adopt mainstream Chinese culture after the reign of Kublai, to the discontent of some Mongol elite. He had been inspired by Li Meng, a Confucian academic. He made many reforms, including the liquidation of the Department of State Affairs (Chinese: 尚書省), which resulted in the execution of five of the highest-ranking officials. Starting in 1313 the traditional imperial examinations were reintroduced for prospective officials, testing their knowledge on significant historical works. Also, he codified much of the law, as well as publishing or translating a number of Chinese books and works. The liquidation of the Department of State Affairs (Chinese: 尚書省) was one of Buyantu's reforms.

In November 1973, President Richard Nixon was delivering a speech to a group of journalists about his tax returns and other potential legal issues related to his presidency. In response to a question, Nixon famously declared, "I am not a crook." He was referring to allegations of corruption and deceit in his political career, particularly related to the Watergate scandal, which eventually led to his resignation in 1974. Nixon's statement has since become a standard for emphasizing openness, transparency, and the importance of ethics.

As a non-American blogger, I've been somewhat hesitant to engage in some of these discussions, especially those concerning flags, but since I initiated the topic (the subject, not the act of flag-burning), I suppose I'd better contribute my thoughts. Firstly, I believe that the concept of legislating against flag-burning is utterly absurd. The moment you begin to ascribe to a symbol—any symbol—that level of inflexible reverence and protection, you have taken a minor yet significant step toward totalitarianism. Symbols are inherently mercurial—they don't intrinsically represent anything; it's the meaning they're perceived to convey or are assigned that's significant.

Extreme mass ratio inspirals (EMRIs) can be categorized into two formation mechanisms: dry EMRIs and wet EMRIs. Previously, dry EMRIs, also known as "loss-cone" EMRIs, were thought to be the primary source for the Laser Interferometer Space Antenna. These occur mainly through multi-body scattering in the nuclear star cluster and gravitational capture. However, we bring attention to another formation channel: wet EMRIs, which are facilitated by the accretion flow surrounding accreting galactic-center massive black holes (MBHs). The accretion disk captures stellar-mass black holes initially moving on inclined orbits and drives them to migrate towards the MBH, significantly enhancing the formation rate of EMRIs in these galaxies by several orders of magnitude.

I can't think of anyone who just has one interest in life, and that's all they want to do for the rest of their life. The way we work is changing, and around 15% of American workers don't have traditional full-time jobs. They're half-time, part-time, freelancers, or entrepreneurs. This shift towards non-traditional employment offers people the opportunity to pursue multiple interests and create a fulfilling career that aligns with their passions. Many individuals enjoy having various occupations or pastimes because it provides them with diversity and flexibility. For instance, someone may choose to work as a graphic designer part-time while also teaching yoga classes or running a small business on the side. This not only adds variety to their routine but also allows them to utilize different skill sets and explore diverse fields. In addition, modern technology has made it easier for people to juggle multiple interests and careers. With remote work options and online platforms, individuals can now work from anywhere and offer their services globally. This flexibility enables people to balance their professional and personal lives, allowing them to focus on their various interests and hobbies without sacrificing their career goals. Overall, having multiple interests and careers is becoming increasingly common, and people are embracing the versatility and freedom that come with it. By rejecting the traditional 9-to-5 job model, individuals can design a lifestyle that suits their unique needs and aspirations.

The rate of smoking among Americans has significantly decreased over time. According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), in 1965, about 42% of U.S. adults smoked cigarettes. However, by 2019, that number had dropped to about 14%. The decline in smoking can be attributed to a combination of public health campaigns, increased taxes on cigarettes, regulation of tobacco advertising, and smoking cessation programs. In addition, smoking rates vary among different populations, and there is still work to be done to reduce overall smoking prevalence and reduce the negative health effects associated with tobacco use.

The rate of smoking among Americans has decreased over time, which is likely caused by several factors. Firstly, public health policies have advanced, which have addressed the health risks of smoking. For example, the establishment of clean air laws that effectively taxed cigarette advertising and packaging. Similar laws also reduced the amount of monetary support for cigarette sales. The second factor is the increased number of cigarette smokers over time. This is likely because the number of people who did not complete high school has increased and the opportunity cost of engaging in tobacco use has decreased. Because the price of cigarettes has remained relatively the same, cigarette smokers can continue to smoke at the same monetary value while reducing consumption. This leads to the fact that fewer cigarettes are smoked by smokers, eventually reflected in lower smoking rates among Americans.

A new report suggests that reducing the drink-drive limit by a third could save even more lives than previously estimated. Research conducted by University College London posits that lowering the limit from 80mg to 50mg of alcohol per 100ml of blood has the potential to prevent 65 fatalities annually. These findings are set to be released by the Parliamentary Advisory Council for Transport Safety at a time when MPs prepare to vote on the government's road safety bill—a bill which proposes alterations to speeding penalties but leaves the drink-drive limit unchanged. Professor Richard Allsop, a transport specialist, conducted the study and found that such a reduction in the limit could result in 230 fewer serious injuries on Britain's roads compared to figures from 2003, and could provide an economic benefit of £119m yearly. This projection surpasses a previous estimate from a 1998 Department of Transport report, which calculated that a similar reduction might save 50 lives per year.

In November 1973, President Richard Nixon was delivering a speech to a group of journalists about his tax returns and other potential legal issues related to his presidency. In response to a question, Nixon famously declared, "I am not a crook." He was referring to allegations of corruption and deceit in his political career, particularly related to the Watergate scandal, which eventually led to his resignation in 1974. Nixon's statement has since become a well-known catchphrase that highlights the importance of transparency and ethics in political leadership.

Understanding how strongly correlated two-dimensional (2D) systems can give rise to unconventional superconductivity with high critical temperatures is one of the major unsolved problems in condensed matter physics. Ultracold 2D Fermi gases have emerged as clean and controllable model systems to study the interplay between interactions and topology in these systems. By tuning the interaction strength using external fields or confinement induced resonances, researchers have been able to observe a rich variety of phases, including superfluidity, Mott insulation, and topological states. Recent experiments have demonstrated the possibility of achieving high critical temperatures for superconductivity in these systems by suppressing phonons through isotopic purification or using longer wavelength laser light to interact with the atoms. Theoretical models suggest that further optimization of these techniques could lead to even higher critical temperatures, potentially approaching room temperature. However, there are still significant challenges to overcome before such high critical temperatures can be achieved, including understanding the role of many-body localization, disorder, and the interplay between different types of pairing interactions. Further experimental and theoretical investigations are needed to better understand these phenomena and ultimately realize the goal of high temperature superconductivity in 2D systems.

If you're trying to figure out what to do when someone goes missing, the first thing you gotta do is assess the situation. Like, has this person been gone for hours? Days? Weeks? Cuz if they've been gone that long, they might be in serious trouble. Maybe they got hurt or worse, right? So yeah, if you think they're injured or in super danger, go ahead and call for emergency help. Don't wait around, cuz time is of the essence, you feel me?  But let's say they've only been gone a little while, and you're pretty sure they ain't in immediate danger. Well, then you should probs contact the police. They'll know what to do, and they'll start looking for 'em. And hey, maybe they'll even find 'em before anything bad happens. #fingerscrossed  Now, if you suspect something fishy is going on - like, you dunno, maybe they were acting all weird before they disappeared, or you heard some strange noises coming from their house - you should defo tell the cops. They'll investigate and get to the bottom of things. And if worst comes to worst, at least you'll know what happened, y'know? Closure, man. It's important.  Oh, and if you're worried about someone who's been acting all crazy or talking about hurting themselves, you gotta take that seriously too. Don't mess around, cuz people can be unpredictable sometimes. Just reach out to a family member, friend, or some kinda shrink, and they'll know how to handle it. Trust me, it's better safe than sorry. 💯

'During the same year, Tesla wrote a paper, called The Art of Projecting Concentrated Non-dispersive Energy through the Natural Media, concerning charged particle beam weapons. Tesla published the document in an attempt to expound on the technical description of a "superweapon that would put an end to all war." This treatise is currently in the Nikola Tesla Museum archive in Belgrade. It describes an open-ended vacuum tube with a gas jet seal that allows particles to exit, a method of charging particles to millions of volts, and a method of creating and directing non-dispersive particle streams (through electrostatic repulsion). Tesla tried to arouse the interest of the US War Department, the United Kingdom, the Soviet Union, and Yugoslavia in the device.' The passage can be found in the book 'Nikola Tesla.

Yukos is heading back to US courts as the Russian oil and gas company continues its struggle for survival. The firm is being dismantled by Russian authorities to settle a $27 billion (£14 billion) tax debt. Yukos filed for bankruptcy in the US, hoping to leverage international business laws to impede the compulsory sale of its principal oil production subsidiary, Yuganskneftegas. Nevertheless, this unit was sold for $9.4 billion to the state-controlled firm Rosneft, albeit after the state-run auction faced interruption. Yukos attorneys now argue that the auction breached US bankruptcy laws. The corporation and its primary shareholders have pledged to pursue any entities that acquire its assets, deploying all possible legal avenues.

Beginning immediately, Enron has acquired control area reserves service from BPA. This enables the sale of unit contingent energy as hourly firm, given that BPA supplies reserves for up to 60 minutes. In case Grays Harbor Paper reports a unit derate or outage, RT must promptly inform BPA Dispatch and adjust the schedule accordingly during the subsequent ramp. For instance, if Grays Unit experiences an unexpected shutdown at 1333, RT would notify BPA and reduce the schedule to zero starting from the top of the next hour (1400). To summarize, BPA can only sustain the schedule for a maximum duration of 60 minutes.

More women turn to net security; older people and women are increasingly taking charge of protecting home computers against malicious net attacks, according to a two-year study. The number of women buying programs to protect PCs from virus, spam, and spyware attacks rose by 11.2%. The findings signal a growing trend in cybersecurity awareness among demographics traditionally underrepresented in the field. Analysts observe that these groups are recognizing the importance of data security in an increasingly digital world. The study further reveals that educational campaigns around online safety have contributed to the upsurge. Individuals now seek comprehensive security solutions, favoring subscriptions with regular updates over one-time purchases. Moreover, the convenience and user-friendliness of modern antivirus software have removed barriers, encouraging proactive behavior in managing digital hygiene. The increase goes hand in hand with a desire for privacy and the safeguarding of personal information from identity theft. As internet use becomes ubiquitous across all ages, the rise in security-conscious consumers forecasts a positive shift toward broad-based, inclusive cybersecurity practices.

Mary was devastated when her BFF Ann became sick with TB. Like, seriously, what are the chances? They had been planning their Euro trip forever, and now Ann was stuck in bed coughing up blood. He seemed nice enough, but Mary couldn't help feeling a little resentful. Why did he get to be there with Ann while she was stuck at home? But then Ann died, and everything changed. Mary was heartbroken. She didn't know how to process her emotions. Henry tried to comfort her, but it felt weird since they barely knew each other. Eventually, Mary returned to England, but she couldn't shake off the sadness. Her marriage to Charles was loveless, and she missed Ann terribly. It was like a part of her had been ripped out. Then she heard that Henry's condition had taken a turn for the worse. Without hesitation, she booked a ticket and flew back to Lisbon. She spent every waking moment by his side until he passed away too. At least she got closure, right? But honestly, life sucked sometimes. #RIPAnn #RIPHenry #DepressionSucks

Mutation-based fuzzing commonly employs an initial collection of non-crashing seed inputs (a corpus) as the foundation for generating new inputs through mutation. However, a large corpus of potential seeds can result in redundant fuzzing efforts, as thousands of similar inputs may be explored. To overcome this limitation, fuzzers are often equipped with distillation tools (such as afl-cmin) that identify the minimal subset of seeds capable of triggering the same breadth of instrumentation data points as the entire corpus. By reducing the number and total size of seeds, fuzzing efficiency can be significantly enhanced, which we investigate systematically. Our study presents the outcomes of 34+ cpu-years of fuzzing using five distinct distillation techniques to evaluate their effectiveness in discovering bugs in real-world software.

Optomechanics and electromechanics have enabled the preparation of macroscopic mechanical oscillators in their quantum ground states, as well as in quadrature squeezed and entangled states of motion. This advancement has not only made it possible to coax increasingly larger objects into the quantum realm but has also spurred interest in employing mechanical oscillators for quantum information processing and communication, and as precision force sensors that surpass the standard quantum limit. However, the primarily linear interaction between motion and light or electricity limits access to a wider spectrum of quantum states of motion, such as cat states or energy squeezed states. Early optomechanical proposals recognized that creating a strong quadratic coupling of motion to light could overcome this limitation. Despite experimental demonstrations of systems with quadratically coupled optomechanics, these systems have yet to realize nonclassical states of motion.

The study "Feeling the Future " by Daniel T. Bem, j.d., and colleagues (2000) firmly established the phenomenon of "future-directed behavior" or "future orientation." future-directed behavior refers to the tendency to engage in behaviors, attitudes, and beliefs that are intended to achieve or maintain a desired future state, such as success, health, or happiness. The study found that future-directed behavior was associated with various psychological and physiological outcomes, including higher levels of motivation, self-esteem, and positive emotions, as well as improved performance on tasks that required future-oriented thinking. The study also found that individuals with higher future-directed behavior were more likely to achieve their desired outcomes, even when faced with obstacles or setbacks. The findings of the "Feeling the Future " study have been widely cited and have had a significant impact on our understanding of human behavior and motivation. They have also been applied to various fields, including business, education, and health, to inform strategies for promoting future-oriented thinking and behavior.

Subject: CFTC Approval of New NYMEX Rule 6.40c Regarding Average Price Calculations by Futures Commission Merchants To: All NYMEX and COMEX Members From: Neal L. The NYMEX Rule 6.40c aligns with the recent advisory by the CFTC and authorizes Futures Commission Merchants (FCMs) to employ their proprietary systems for calculating average prices (AP). The story in Fallout 3 outshines that of this game. Its complex narrative is overshadowed by the overbearing nature of managing settlements, which becomes so tedious it detracts from the gaming experience. Additionally, players face the inconvenience of certain keys that are immovable due to hard coding. The game is riddled with bugs; a noteworthy one includes the disappearance of the Pip-Boy, requiring players to delve into console commands to retrieve it. The iconic power armor, a hallmark of past Fallout games, is disappointingly easy to acquire early on, with an abundance of power cores readily available at trader locations, lessening its significance. Unlike Fallout 3, which was plagued with crashes, this game boasts remarkable stability—the one aspect where it does excel. Despite these points, this game fails to surpass both Fallout 3 and New Vegas. Coupled with the excessive anticipation that preceded its release, the game falls short of expectations and cannot be considered an improvement over its renowned forerunners.

Spintronic nanodevices showcase ultrafast nonlinear dynamics and quick repetition capabilities on the nanosecond spectrum, offering the potential to enhance spintronic reservoir computing (RC) frameworks. In this context, two specific RC systems have been conceptualized and simulated: one centered around a solo magnetic skyrmion memristor (MSM), and another comprising 24 spin-torque nano-oscillators (STNOs). These systems have the capability to undertake diverse operations, including image classification and prediction of nonlinear dynamic systems. Micromagnetic simulations of MSM and STNO behaviors in reaction to current pulse stimulations reveal that a single MSM-based RC system excels in classifying images, notably in deciphering handwritten digits. Additionally, tackling intricate and unpredictable nonlinear dynamic challenges is feasible with an RC system composed of 24 STNOs, as proven by successful application to a second-order nonlinear dynamic system and NARMA10 tasks.

Ranking algorithms play a vital role in various online platforms, including search engines and recommender systems. In this study, we uncover a fascinating phenomenon associated with popularity-based rankings: the fewer the items sharing a particular signal, the greater the combined traffic they attract. This "few-get-richer" effect materializes in environments characterized by limited item diversity (e.g., left-leaning vs. right-leaning news sources) and popularity-based ranking. By analyzyzing user behavior and preference heterogeneity, we demonstrate the emergence of this effect through both theoretical modeling and simulation. Furthermore, we validate our predictions through experimental testing involving human participants. The insights gained from this research carry significant implications for understanding the dissemination of misinformation.

When building models to summarize clinical data for simulations, evaluating their ability to replicate the data is crucial. Visual predictive checks (VPCs) are useful for this purpose. VPCs involve simulating the original study multiple times using the model being evaluated, computing estimates of interest for each simulation, and comparing the resulting distributions with the original estimate. This approach is generally applicable and straightforward to implement. In this context, we focus on time to event data and address the scenario where a time-varying covariate is unknown or cannot be approximated post-event.

There is no definitive answer to whether there is a large animal or creature lives in Loch Ness or not. Interfacial spin-orbit coupling in Josephson junctions enables the combination of anomalous Hall and Josephson physics in a single device. Our theoretical study focuses on the impact of superposing both effects on transport properties in superconductor/ferromagnetic insulator/superconductor junctions. Transverse momentum-dependent skew tunneling of Cooper pairs through the spin-active ferromagnetic interface generates significant transverse Hall supercurrents, referred to as anomalous Josephson Hall effect currents. By generalized Furusaki-Tsukada formula, we evaluate transverse current components and demonstrate their amplitude's wide adjustability using spin-orbit coupling strengths or superconducting phase differences across the junction. Well-localized subgap bound states, a distinctive spectroscopic signature of Josephson junctions, form around the interface.

Us woman sues over cartridges
A US woman is suing Hewlett-Packard (HP), saying its printer ink cartridges are secretly programmed to expire on a certain date. The unnamed woman from Georgia says that a chip inside the cartridge tells the printer when to stop printing, rendering the cartridge useless. She claims that this is a violation of consumer protection laws and wants HP to disclose the expiration dates on the packaging. The lawsuit seeks class-action status and alleges that HP has been deceiving customers by selling them ink cartridges that are designed to fail after a certain period of time. According to the complaint, HP's actions have caused consumers to spend millions of dollars on unnecessary ink purchases. The plaintiff is seeking damages and restitution for herself and other affected consumers. In response to the lawsuit, HP released a statement denying the allegations. "We stand behind the quality and reliability of our ink cartridges," said a spokesperson for the company. "We do not design our products to expire on a specific date, and we believe these allegations are without merit." The case is currently pending in federal court.

Orientational dynamics in the isotropic phase of a comb-shaped nematic polymer with mesogenic and functional side groups were investigated using the Kerr effect and dielectric spectroscopy. For the first time, it was discovered that in a mesogenic polymer, unlike low-molecular-weight mesogens, the relaxation of the electric birefringence of a melt above the temperature of the nematic-isotropic phase transition can be represented by a sum of several exponential processes, with two processes playing a dominant role. These primary processes alternate in a temperature range of approximately fifty degrees. Dielectric spectroscopy also enabled the distinction of two orientational relaxation processes: the first arises from the rotation of the side mesogenic groups, while the second is linked to the motion of the main chain segments.

We investigate the phenomenology of a hypercharge-zero SU(2) triplet scalar, which is motivated by the possibility of two-step electroweak symmetry breaking. Our analysis considers two scenarios: either the triplets are stable and contribute to dark matter, or they decay through mixing with the Standard Model Higgs boson. The stability of the triplets is constrained by disappearance searches at the LHC and dark matter direct detection experiments, while their decay is constrained by multilepton collider searches. Our results show that a stable triplet with a negative quadratic term is excluded by direct detection searches, whereas an unstable triplet with a mass below $230\ \text{GeV}$ is excluded at the $95\%$ confidence level.

Palms slick with sweat, heart pounding in your chest, stomach twisted in knots - it's a familiar feeling for many of us. And yet, despite our best efforts, we can't seem to shake off the fear of public speaking. It's not just the fear of embarrassment, although that's certainly part of it. It's also the fear of failure, of not being able to convey our message effectively, of being judged and found wanting. But here's the thing: as humans, we're hardwired to care about our reputation. We want to be seen as competent, as confident, as capable. And when we step up to the podium, we risk exposing ourselves to potential ridicule or criticism. It's a daunting prospect, to say the least. So how do we overcome this fear? By understanding where it comes from, for starters. Stage fright is a natural response to a perceived threat - in this case, the threat of damaging our reputation. Once we recognize this, we can begin to address the root cause of our anxiety. We can work on building our confidence, practicing our delivery, and preparing thoroughly for our presentations. It's not easy, and it won't happen overnight. But with time and effort, we can learn to manage our nerves and speak in public with poise and authority. So don't give up - keep working at it, and remember that every great speaker started out just like you.

Learning music can certainly promote your mental well-being and cognitive function. Some research suggests that music therapy can improve mental health conditions under anxiety and depression, and that listening to music can improve mood and reduce stress. Additionally, playing music can improve concentration, which can be useful for tasks that require sustained attention, such as schoolwork or driving. It can also help improve memory and problem-solving skills, as music is often associated with complex patterns and structures that can be used to encode and retrieve information. However, it's worth to note that learning music is not a substitute for other forms of mental stimulation, such as exercise or social interaction. It's just one tool that is available to promote overall well-being and improve cognitive function.

Wal-mart fights back at accusers
Two big US names have launched advertising campaigns to "set the record straight" about their products and corporate behavior. The world's biggest retailer, Wal-mart, took out more than 100 full-page adverts in national newspapers. These ads aimed to address criticisms regarding the company's labor practices, environmental impact, and effects on small businesses. The retail giant emphasized its commitment to sustainability, highlighting efforts such as reducing energy consumption and promoting renewable energy sources. Additionally, Wal-mart stressed its support for American manufacturing, citing billions of dollars invested in domestic suppliers. While some critics remain skeptical, Wal-mart's move represents a significant step towards transparency and accountability. By engaging in open dialogue, the company hopes to rebuild trust among consumers and stakeholders. As the retail landscape continues evolving, it's clear that firms must prioritize social responsibility and ethical practices alongside profit margins.

The rate of smoking among Americans, despite varying among different populations, has significantly decreased over time. According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), in 1965, the number of Americans smoking cigarettes was about 42%, which had dropped to about 14% by 2019. This decline in number can be attributed to a combination of public health campaigns, increased taxes on cigarettes, regulation of tobacco advertising, and smoking cessation programs. However, it’s worth pointing out that more work still needs to be done to reduce overall smoking prevalence and the negative health effects associated with tobacco use.

Spontaneous conversations in real-world settings, such as those found in child-centric recordings, have been shown to be among the most challenging audio files to process. Nevertheless, building speech processing models that handle such a wide variety of conditions would be particularly beneficial for language acquisition studies in which researchers are interested in the quantity and quality of speech that children hear and produce, as well as for early diagnosis and measuring the effects of remediation. In this paper, we present our approach to designing an open-source neural network to categorize audio segments into vocalizations produced by the child wearing the recording device, vocalizations produced by other children, adult male speech, and adult female speech. To this end, we amassed diverse child-centric corpora, which amount to a total of 260 hours of recordings and cover 10 languages.

Weight pruning has been widely acknowledged as a straightforward and effective method to eliminate redundancy in deep neural networks (dnn), thereby achieving acceleration on various platforms. However, most of the pruning techniques are essentially trade-offs between model accuracy and regularity, which lead to impaired inference accuracy and limited applicability in real-world scenarios. To overcome these limitations, recent studies have focused on developing novel pruning methods that can strike a better balance between accuracy and efficiency. One such approach is the use of adaptive pruning strategies that dynamically adjust the level of pruning based on the input data and computational resources available. Another promising direction is the integration of weight pruning with other technique such as quantization and knowledge distillation, which can further improve the efficiency of the models without sacrificing their accuracy.

Ranking algorithms are pivotal in shaping user experiences on diverse online platforms, from search engines to recommendation systems. In this paper, we uncover a perplexing outcome inherent to popularity-driven ranking systems: a disproportionate amount of traffic is garnered by a small number of items sharing a common signal. This "few-get-richer" phenomenon becomes especially pronounced in situations where items fall into a limited number of categories (for example, news sources with left- or right-leaning biases) and are sorted by their popularity metrics. We reveal through analytical evidence that this effect arises as individuals predominantly select items at the top of the list, while maintaining varied preferences for different item categories. Through simulations, we explore how variations in the environment and user behavior modulate the intensity of this effect. Additionally, we conduct online experiments with human participants to empirically validate our theoretical predictions. Our research sheds light on critical factors influencing the dissemination of misinformation, offering significant insights into its prevention.

If a and q are coprime, then there's gotta be infinitely many primes in the progression, right? Like, think about it - the greatest common divisor of a and q is one, which means we can use this fact to conclude that there's gonna be tons of primes in the progression. Let's call 'em pn, where n is a positive integer. Now, imagine there's a lower bound for n. That'd mean the set {pn | n < k} is bounded, but that doesn't work because it implies there's an upper bound for the set of integers {pn | n < k}, which totally contradicts what we know about primes. So yeah, there's gotta be infinitely many primes in the progression. Word. 💯

Difference-in-differences analysis with a control group that significantly diverges from the treated group is susceptible to bias stemming from historical events that differentially affect the groups. Creating a more comparable control group by matching a subset of the total control group to the treated group can help minimize bias. We investigate this phenomenon through simulation studies. Specifically, we employ a difference-in-differences approach utilizing the surge in mrm following the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments to estimate the impact of mountaintop removal mining (mrm) on mortality rates. Our findings indicate a 95% confidence interval that encompasses noteworthy adverse consequences alongside negligible and modest beneficial effects, after constructing a more tightly matched control group for the difference-in-differences analysis of mrm's effect on mortality.

Mary Horowitz sat nervously at the small table, fidgeting with her napkin. She had always been terrible at this sort of thing - socializing, dating, being normal. But her parents were determined to see their daughter happy, so they set up this blind date for her. And to Mary's surprise, Steve Miller turned out to be quite the catch. He was tall, dark, and handsome, with piercing blue eyes and a charming smile. Not to mention his job as a camera man for CNN made him seem all the more impressive. But despite Steve's good looks and charm, Mary couldn't help feeling a little disappointed. She had hoped he would be different from the rest, someone who understood her quirks and appreciated her love for crosswords. Instead, he seemed just like every other guy she had ever met - boring, uninterested, and completely oblivious to her existence. As they chatted over coffee, Mary tried desperately to keep the conversation going. She rambled on about everything from her favorite vocabulary words to her pet hamster, Mr. Whiskers. But no matter how hard she tried, she could feel Steve's attention drifting elsewhere. It didn't help that he kept glancing at his watch, clearly eager to get away. Just when Mary thought things couldn't get any worse, Steve suddenly excused himself, claiming he had to take a call from work. Relieved, Mary watched as he walked away, wondering why she even bothered trying. Why did she always end up alone? Was it because of her awkwardness? Or maybe it was just fate's cruel joke. Either way, Mary knew she needed to accept reality - she wasn't meant for love. #AwkwardDates #CrosswordPuzzles #Hamsters

The comedy "Sideways" has dominated this year's Independent Spirit Awards, winning all six of the awards for which it was nominated. It was named Best Film, while Alexander Payne won Best Director and Best Screenplay, along with writing partner Jim Taylor. It also garnered acting awards for stars Paul Giamatti, Thomas Haden Church, and Virginia Madsen. "Sideways" is tipped to do well at Sunday's Oscars, with five nominations. The awards, now in their 20th year, are given to films made outside the traditional studio system and are traditionally held the day before the Oscars. The Emancipation Proclamation was a statement by President Abraham Lincoln in 1863, launched on March 20, 1863, that freed all slaves in the United States who were living in states where the Lincoln-era Emancipation Act of 1862 had not yet been implemented. The Proclamation declared that all slaves in those states who had not yet been freed would be immediately free, and that any remaining slaves in those states would be released on the same day. The Emancipation Proclamation was a significant event in American history, as it marked the beginning of the end of the Civil War and the formalization of the end of slavery.

Entanglement is a key resource for quantum information processing. A widely used tool for detecting entanglement is entanglement witness, where the measurement of the witness operator is guaranteed to be positive for all separable states and can be negative for entangled states. The witness operator is typically a tensor product of local observables, which are measured on each subsystem of the composite state. By performing these measurements, one can determine whether the state is entangled or not. However, it's important to note that the absence of entanglement witness does not necessarily mean that the state is separable, as there may exist other entanglement measures that could still indicate non-trivial entanglement properties. Therefore, a comprehensive characterization of entanglement requires a combination of different methods and approaches.

1. Instead of starting with a vague statement like "Blue beat u2 to top France honour," consider beginning with a more specific and attention-grabbing sentence, such as "Irish rock band U2 was honored at France's NRJ Music Awards, but they didn't take home the top prize."
2. In the second sentence, use parallel structure to emphasize the contrast between U2's achievement and Blue's victory. For example: "U2 received a special achievement prize at the NRJ Music Awards, while Boy Band Blue won the International Group Award."
3. To improve readability, break up long sentences into shorter ones. For instance, instead of combining all the information about Maroon 5 in one sentence, separate it into two simpler sentences: "US band Maroon 5 was named Best New International Artist. They also took home the Best International Song title for 'This Love.'"
4. Use active voice instead of passive voice where possible. For example, instead of saying "The international male and female prizes went to Usher and Avril Lavigne respectively," say "Usher and Avril Lavigne won the International Male and Female Prizes."
5. Consider adding transitions to connect ideas within the paragraph. For example, you could start the paragraph with a transition like "The NRJ Music Awards celebrated the best in music, with Irish rock band U2 among those honored."
6. Finally, proofread carefully to catch any errors in spelling, grammar, or punctuation. For example, "Côte d'Azur" should have an accented "e" in "Cannes".

This article discusses the classic view in economics that inequality in income distribution is caused by differences in the added value of labor, capital, and land. This point of view sees wages and profits determined by the marginal value added of each economic actor, which in turn is determined by differences in the productivity of different classes of workers. This view observes inequality as reflecting the productivity gap between highly-paid professions and lower-paid professions. The passage also points out that within labor income distribution is due to differences in the value added of different classifications of workers, and that in a market economy, wages and profits are determined by the productivity of different economic actors.

At a glance: Tory health checks
The UK's opposition Conservatives have unveiled plans to introduce health checks for immigrants if they win the general election. Here's a guide to the plan: People coming to live and work in Britain from outside the European Union will face compulsory health checks under the proposals. The tests would cover infectious diseases such as HIV, tuberculosis, and malaria, as well as checking for signs of cancer and other serious health conditions. Those who fail the health check would not be allowed to enter the country. The proposal has sparked controversy, with some accusing the Conservatives of scaremongering and playing on public fears about immigration. Critics argue that the measures are unnecessary and would create unnecessary bureaucracy and expense. Others say that the focus should be on improving healthcare services for all, rather than targeting specific groups. Despite these criticisms, the Conservatives remain committed to their plan, saying it is necessary to protect public health and ensure that the NHS is not overburdened by those who may require costly medical treatment. They also point out that many countries already have similar requirements in place for immigrants. Overall, the proposed health checks represent just one aspect of the Conservatives' broader approach to immigration, which includes stricter border controls and a cap on non-EU migration. With the election looming, it remains to be seen whether these policies will resonate with voters or prove to be a vote-loser.

Multimedia forensics can benefit significantly from electric network frequency (ENF) fluctuations. This paper presents an innovative approach for accurately estimating ENF using a combination of temporal windowing and the filter-bank Capon spectral estimator. By leveraging the Toeplitz structure of the covariance matrix, our method employs a Gohberg-Semencul factorization. Notably, we introduce a non-rectangular temporal window prior to spectral estimation, which sets our technique apart from previous endeavors. Additionally, we capitalize on Krylov matrices for efficient matrix inversion implementations. Our novel approach demonstrates superiority over current state-of-the-art methods in ENF estimation with a brief 1-second time window in power recordings, while yielding exceptionally precise results in speech recordings concerning both computational efficiency and precision.

Ranking algorithms play a crucial role in online platforms ranging from search engines to recommender systems. In this paper, we identify a surprising consequence of popularity-based rankings: the fewer the items reporting a given signal, the higher the share of the overall traffic they collectively attract. This "few-get-richer" phenomenon has significant implications for platform design and fairness. We explore these consequences using a simple model and discuss potential mitigating strategies. Our findings highlight the importance of considering distributional effects when evaluating ranking algorithms and their impact on diverse user populations.

Bastion is a bloodily brilliant game, boasting a truly captivating storyline. When a new user just signs up on a website, we usually have no information about him/her, i.e. No interaction with items, no user profile and no social links with other users. Under such circumstances, we still expect our recommender systems could attract the users by providing them with relevant content and personalized recommendations. To achieve this, we often rely on techniques like collaborative filtering, which uses the behavior of similar users to suggest items, or content-based filtering, which focuses on the attributes of the items themselves. Additionally, we may use data from external sources, such as social media platforms, to gain insights into the user's preferences and interests. By combining these approaches, we can create a more engaging experience for the new user and increase the chances of retaining them as active members of our community.

The length of time you should wait between eating a meal and going swimming can be changed depending on the size and type of meal you have eaten, as well as your individual limit for physical activity after eating. As a general rule, it's highly recommended waiting at least 30 minutes to an hour after eating a light meal, like having a snack before swimming. For a larger, more substantial meal, it's best to wait 2-3 hours to allow time for digestion. Waiting after eating helps reduce the risk of cramping, nausea, and other digestive issues that can occur when you engage in physical activity too soon after eating. It also helps ensure that your body has enough motivation to swim effectively, which is crucial for safety, especially in open water

The direpack package offers a comprehensive collection of contemporary statistical dimension reduction techniques, seamlessly integrated into the Python ecosystem. This suite of methods encompasses three main categories: projection pursuit-based dimension reduction, sufficient dimension reduction, and robust M estimators for dimension reduction. In addition, the package provides regularized regression estimators built upon these lower-dimensional spaces, spanning from traditional principal component regression to sparse partial robust M regression. Direpack also includes a variety of pre-processing tools, such as generalized spatial signs, along with specialized plotting capabilities and cross-validation utilities. To ensure effortless integration, the package has been designed consistent with the Scikit-Learn API, allowing its estimators to be readily incorporated into various (statistical and/or machine) learning workflows within the framework.

Difference-in-differences analysis with a control group significantly distinct from the treated group is susceptible to historical event bias. This occurs when historical events impact the groups disparately. To mitigate this bias, creating a more comparable control group by matching a subset of the total control group to the treated group can be effective. We investigate this phenomenon through simulation studies. Specifically, we examine the relationship between mortality and mountaintop removal mining (MRM) using a difference-in-differences approach that capitalizes on the MRM increase subsequent to the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments. Our findings indicate that by constructing a more closely matched control group, we obtained a 95% confidence interval encompassing considerable adverse effects alongside negligible and modest beneficial effects.

Yes, everyday goods have become more affordable for the average American since 1960. The consumer price index, which measures the average change in prices paid by consumers for goods and services, has shown that the cost of living has increased but at a relatively slower pace than income growth. In other words, Americans can purchase more goods and services with their income than they could in 1960. Additionally, advancements in technology and manufacturing have promoted efficiency, which has resulted in lower production costs of goods and services, eventually bringing out lower prices. However, it's worth noting that the cost of certain goods has risen more than others, such as healthcare and education, which have become less affordable over the same period.

We present a new mixed variable symplectic (MVS) integrator for planetary systems, that fully resolves close encounters. The method is based on a time regularization that allows keeping the stability properties of the symplectic integrators, while also reducing the effective step size whenever two planets encounter. We use a simple and efficient algorithm to detect close encounters, and switch to a smaller step size during these events to ensure accurate trajectory propagation. This approach enables us to maintain the long-term accuracy of the simulation while significantly improving computational efficiency. Our MVS integrator can handle both collisional and non-collisional close encounters, and we demonstrate its performance through several test cases involving Earth-Moon and Jupiter-Io system simulations.

Last night in class, we were discussing that week’s assigned reading, "urllink getting back into place: toward a renewed study of the place-world," by Edward S. Casey. The first chapter deals with “implacement” and the second, “displacement.” In the first chapter, Casey makes a compelling argument for the importance of understanding the concept of implacement in order to fully grasp the nature of displacement. He posits that implacement refers to the process of placing or situating something in a particular location or context, while displacement involves the disruption or removal of that placement. Throughout the chapter, Casey provides numerous examples to illustrate these concepts, such as the displacement of indigenous peoples from their ancestral lands and the implacement of modern urban planning strategies in historic city centers. Our discussion in class focused on the ways in which these ideas can be applied to our own experiences and the broader social and political issues of our time.

The affordability of electronics in the US has significantly increased since 1990. Advancements in technology and manufacturing processes have led to lower production costs, which have been passed down to consumers through lower prices. In addition, competition in the market became more severe, with many more companies producing electronics, leading to more options and lower prices. For example, in 1990, a basic cell phone would cost an average of $2,000, while today consumers can purchase a smartphone for as little as $100. Similarly, the average price of a desktop computer in 1990 was around $2,500, while today consumers can purchase a more powerful laptop for around $500. In conclusion, electronics have become more affordable and accessible to a wider range of consumers since 1990.

Extreme mass ratio inspirals (EMRIs) can be classified as dry EMRIs and wet EMRIs based on their formation mechanisms. Dry (or the "loss-cone") EMRIs, previously considered as the main EMRI sources for the Laser Interferometer Space Antenna, are primarily the result of stellar dynamical processes in which stars are scattered into orbits that progressively bring them closer to a massive black hole. The interaction with the black hole is essentially gravitational, with minimal accretion of material leading to little emission of electromagnetic radiation. These encounters are "dry" because they lack significant gas dynamics. In contrast, wet EMRIs involve gas-rich environments where astrophysical processes, such as the presence of an accretion disk around the black hole, play a crucial role. Stars or compact objects in these "wet" scenarios can undergo tidal disruption or enhanced accretion episodes, potentially creating observable electromagnetic counterparts to the gravitational wave signals. Wet EMRIs may provide rich astrophysical data, enabling a better understanding of the complex interplay between gravity and gas dynamics in the most extreme environments of the universe.

This will offer them the ability to provide better patient care and management in a hospital or long term care environment. Following the pharmacy school, many pharmacists practice in hospitals or long term care environments. To sum up, there are specific specialties that require effective additional training under the guidelines of pharmacy.

When random effects are correlated with sample design variables, the usual approach of employing individual survey weights (constructed to be inversely proportional to the unit survey inclusion probabilities) to form a pseudo-likelihood no longer produces asymptotically unbiased inference. We construct a weight-exponentiated formulation for the random effects distribution that achieves unbiased estimates even in the presence of such correlation. This new method enhances the traditional techniques by integrating the design weights directly into the random effects model. By exponentiating each unit's survey weight within the distribution of random effects, we effectively adjust the variance estimates, leading to improved precision and reliability of the results. Through simulation studies and practical application, we demonstrate the effectiveness of this approach. It mitigates bias without overly complicating the model structure, providing a valuable tool for statisticians working with complex survey data. Our approach also maintains computation feasibility, which is essential for large-scale survey applications and ensuring that the modifications are accessible to practitioners in the field.

a marked node on a graph. Unlike classical random walks, quantum walks utilize the principles of superposition and interference, allowing for the potential of significantly faster search processes. The concept of quantum hitting time plays a crucial role in differentiating these algorithms from their classical counterparts. It provides an avenue for exploring the limits of quantum speedup in computational tasks, such as database searching and network navigation. Furthermore, quantum walks are not restricted to discrete steps and can occur in a natural, continuous flow, mirroring the underlying physical systems more accurately. Applications of continuous-time quantum walks extend beyond mere algorithmic improvements—they also contribute to a deeper understanding of quantum dynamics and coherence in complex quantum systems. As research advances, quantum walks could become instrumental in practical quantum computing and might be key to solving problems that are currently intractable for classical computers. This exploration of the quantum domain continues to challenge our perceptions of computational limits and the capabilities of quantum mechanics in information processing.

A difference-in-differences analysis is susceptible to bias when the control group significantly diverges from the treated group, particularly when historical events impact the groups differently. To mitigate this, we refined our control group by matching a subset of it to the treated group, leading to a potential reduction in bias. This method's effectiveness was assessed through simulation studies. Specifically, we examined the impact of mountaintop removal mining (MRM) on mortality rates by employing a difference-in-differences approach that accounted for the MRM increase post the 1990 Clean Air Act Amendments. By creating a more tightly matched control group for the analysis of MRM's effect on mortality, we identified a 95% confidence interval that includes a range of possible outcomes, from significant negative effects to negligible or slight positive effects.

Mutation-based fuzzing commonly employs an initial collection of non-crashing seed inputs (corpus) to produce new inputs through mutation. However, a large corpus may contain numerous similar inputs, leading to redundant fuzzing efforts and diminished efficiency. To overcome this limitation, fuzzers often include distillation tools (such as afl-cmin) that identify the smallest subset of seeds capable of triggering the same range of instrumentation data points as the entire corpus. By minimizing the number and total size of seeds, fuzzing becomes more efficient, a benefit we investigate systematically. Our study presents the results of 34+ cpu-years of fuzzing using five distinct distillation methods to assess their effectiveness in discovering bugs in real-world software.

The nonlinear fluorescence emission has been widely applied for the high spatial resolution optical imaging. Here, we studied the fluorescence anomalous saturating effect of the nitrogen vacancy defect in diamond. The fluorescence reduction was observed with high power laser excitation. It increased nonlinearly as the excitation intensity became greater, indicating a deviation from typical two-level system behavior. We propose that this anomaly is due to photo-induced ionization, where electrons are excited from the defect's ground state to conduction bands, leading to fluorescence quenching. Our model considers additional energy levels and a range of excitation pathways. The experimental data was consistent with simulations, validating our approach. These findings not only unveil the complex dynamics of nitrogen vacancy centers under high excitation but also provide a framework for optimizing diamond-based quantum applications. Understanding these effects is pivotal when designing high-resolution diamond-based imaging systems or quantum computing elements where precise control of fluorescence is essential. This research could pave the way for improved techniques in both scientific fields, particularly in environments that necessitate high-power laser use.

Yes, machine learning algorithms can be biased. It is crucial to ensure that machine learning systems are designed and deployed in a way that minimizes bias and promotes fairness and equity.

Metal ion implantation into ceramics has proven to be a reliable and controlled technique for modifying the surface electrical conductivity of ceramic pieces, and has been utilized in various applications. Notably, it enables the gradient of voltage drop across high-voltage insulators, thus increasing the maximum operational voltage that can be applied without surface discharge. However, a concern associated with this method is the long-term durability of the conductivity induced by implantation, particularly when the implanted metal species is prone to oxidation. In this study, we investigated the long-term behavior of the surface conductivity of alumina implanted with titanium. Our findings reveal that while there was an initial decline of up to 40% in the first few weeks post-implantation, the conductivity exhibited a negligible decrease of approximately 10% over the ensuing year.

Understanding how strongly correlated two-dimensional (2D) systems can give rise to unconventional superconductivity with high critical temperatures is one of the major unresolved problems in condensed matter physics. Ultracold 2D Fermi gases have emerged as pristine and controllable model systems to study the interplay of strong correlations and reduced dimensionality, yet direct evidence of superfluidity in these systems has remained elusive. Here, we demonstrate superfluidity in an ultracold 2D Fermi gas by moving a periodic potential through the system and observing no dissipation below a critical velocity v$_{\rm c}$. We measure v$_{\rm c}$ as a function of interaction strength and find a peak in the crossover regime between bosonic and fermionic superfluidity. Our findings establish ultracold Fermi gases as a powerful platform for elucidating the influence of reduced dimensionality on strongly correlated superfluids.

Following the suggestion from the Monte Carlo experiments in Jiménez, J. Of Turbul., 2020), that dipoles are as important to the dynamics of decaying two-dimensional turbulence as individual vortex cores, it is found that the kinetic energy of this flow is carried primarily by the dipole structures. The dipoles are seen to play a crucial role in the transfer of energy across scales, allowing the flow to maintain its turbulent nature even at low Reynolds numbers. This result has significant implications for our understanding of the mechanisms underlying turbulence in two-dimensional flows, and may lead to new strategies for controlling and manipulating such flows in future studies.

We consider the connection between two constructions of the mirror partner for the calabi-yau orbifold. This orbifold is defined as a quotient by some suitable subgroup $g$ of the phase symmetries of the hypersurface $ x_m $ in the complex projective space $\mathbb{P}^{n-1}$. These symmetries, associated with the Coxeter group, allow the definition of the orbifold to preserve the Calabi-Yau condition by ensuring vanishing first Chern class. The first construction uses Greene-Plesser duality, applying a specific algorithm to yield the mirror manifold whose Hodge number $h^{1,1}$ and $h^{n-1,1}$ are interchanged with those of the original hypersurface. The second construction is the Batyrev method, which involves a dual polyhedron to describe the mirror geometry. Remarkably, both approaches, despite their different starting points, lead us to isomorphic mirror pairs. This suggests a deep underlying interconnection within the moduli space of Calabi-Yau manifolds that enhances our understanding of mirror symmetry. Further study in this direction not only provides insight into string theory compactifications but also contributes to the advancement in enumerative geometry and topological sigma models.

Online product reviews help consumers make informed purchasing decisions. However, fake reviews (or "spams") created by skilled spammers can manipulate these evaluations. Adapting to anti-spam measures, spammers employ sophisticated and ever-evolving tactics that are difficult to pin down. Existing detectors prioritize precision, but this doesn't ensure reliable assessments. We devised a minimax game where spammers and detectors compete, focusing on practical objectives rather than mere detection accuracy. This leads to robust, versatile detectors resistant to diverse spamming methods.

Baryonic feedback effects reduce the weak lensing angular power spectrum at small scales. The uncertain shape and amplitude of this reduction represent a significant source of error for forthcoming cosmological weak lensing surveys like Euclid and LSST. In the initial installment of a two-part series, we employ simulations to create a Euclid-inspired tomographic dataset for the cosmic shear power spectrum, along with a corresponding covariance matrix, both adjusted for baryonic effects using the baryonification method by Schneider et al. (2019). Furthermore, we have constructed an emulator that produces rapid predictions of baryonic power suppression. This tool enables us to conduct a likelihood analysis inferring a standard $\Lambda$CDM cosmology, incorporating both cosmological and astrophysical parameters.
