A former rugby league international who switched to union in 2000, Robinson will lead England against Australia at Twickenham at 14:30 GMT, followed by Great Britain's rugby league team taking on Australia in the Tri-Nations Tournament final at 18:15 GMT. "Beating the Australians in both games would be an immense accomplishment, particularly for league," Robinson noted. England has the opportunity to secure its third consecutive autumn international victory, building on previous wins over Canada and South Africa, while also exacting revenge for June's 51-15 defeat to the Wallabies. Moreover, Great Britain could break a 34-year losing streak against Australia with a victory at Elland Road.

We introduce a novel mixed variable symplectic (MVS) integrator for planetary systems that accurately resolves close encounters. Our method is founded on a time regularization technique that preserves the stability attributes of symplectic integrators while adaptively decreasing the effective step size during planetary encounters. By employing a high-order MVS scheme, we can integrate with substantial time steps in regions unaffected by close encounters. Our algorithm efficiently handles near-collisions (with a mutual separation of a few percent of the physical radius) utilizing the same time step as in weakly perturbed scenarios, such as the solar system. In a comprehensive analysis, we demonstrate the long-term behavior of our method on systems consisting of six super-Earths undergoing intense scattering over 50 kyr. Our findings indicate that, compared to hybrid approaches like Mercury, our algorithm achieves superior energy conservation at an equal computational cost.

This study explores the dynamics of multi-agent systems with limited visibility. It focuses on systems where agents can be categorized into groups with matching state transition structures. These agents can thus be standardized using a singular template. Leveraging this template, we develop a scalable supervision model that remains efficient irrespective of the number of agents, eliminating the need for recalibration when agents are modified. Our contribution extends previous findings to contexts of partial observation, by identifying key conditions that ensure both safety and optimal leniency within the scalable, least restrictive supervisory framework. An empirical case is also presented to demonstrate the efficacy of our scalable supervisory approach.

Overall, the application of deep learning in wireless communications has opened up new possibilities for advancing the field and enhancing the user experience.

Novel approaches, perspectives, and challenges in measuring and controlling open quantum systems using sequential schemes are presented. We explore how comparable protocols, which rely on both repeated quantum measurements and dynamical decoupling control pulses, can enable us to: (i) mitigate the effects of decoherence on quantum dynamics in line with Zeno's physics. (ii) accurately predict the probability of transferring a quantum system to a desired quantum state through stochastic sequential measurements. (iii) efficiently reconstruct the spectral density of environmental noise sources by orthogonalising their filter functions in the frequency domain, tailoring them to our designed quantum sensor. Accomplishing these goals will significantly enhance our ability to study and manipulate open quantum systems, thereby advancing quantum science and technology.

Deep learning has effectively addressed numerous challenges beyond the capabilities of traditional heuristic methods. Its applications in wireless communication have proven successful, despite the fact that existing radio systems are generally well-understood and optimized algorithms exist for various tasks. Although some progress has been made through learning individual components of a receiver separately, a more effective strategy involves simultaneously learning the entire receiver system. However, this often leads to a complex nonlinear problem where implementing an ideal solution becomes impracticable. In response, we suggest utilizing a deep fully convolutional neural network (deeprx) capable of executing the complete receiver pipeline – from frequency domain signal streams to unencoded bits in compliance with 5G standards. Our method ensures precise channel estimation by carefully designing the convolutional neural network's inputs using both data and pilot symbols.

Deep learning has successfully tackled a multitude of problems previously inaccessible to heuristic algorithms. It has carved a niche in the realm of wireless communications, despite current radio systems being highly sophisticated with optimal algorithms available for numerous operations. Gains have been realized by applying learning techniques to individual receiver components, yet an integrated approach—learning the entire receiver simultaneously—proves to be more effective. However, such an approach typically presents a complex nonlinear challenge, rendering the ideal solution impractical to execute. In response, we introduce a robust deep fully convolutional neural network, named deeprx, designed to process the entire reception pipeline, from the frequency domain signal to the decoding of uncoded bits, in compliance with 5G standards. To ensure precise channel estimation, we meticulously construct the neural network's input by integrating both data and pilot symbols in a strategic manner.

Electrons are typically thought to possess a single type of kinetic energy, but what if they could have more? Could their spin and charge contribute to their energetics, or perhaps interactions with other electrons? In one dimension, the Tomonaga-Luttinger liquid (TLL) model effectively captures the behavior of interacting electrons at low energies, but experimental observations beyond this linear regime have been scarce. To address this knowledge gap, we employed a tunneling spectroscopy technique to measure many-body modes in gated 1D wires. Our experiments revealed two distinct Fermi seas at high energies, corresponding to spin and charge excitations, as well as the emergence of three additional 1D replica modes that become more pronounced with decreasing wire length. By varying the amount of 1D inter-subband screening, we were able to modify the effective interaction strength within the wires by over 45%, providing valuable insights into the complex dynamics of interacting electrons in 1D systems.

Science shows that bumblebees are excellent flyers and are capable of flying at relatively high speeds (up to 15-20 miles per hour) and for long distances (up to several miles). They can also fly in a variety of weather conditions and can navigate complex environments by using visual cues, odors, and other sensory information. Research has shown that bumblebee wings generate lift and thrust similarly to fixed-wing aircraft, with the wings moving as a single unit to generate lift, and changing shape to generate thrust. Despite their relatively small size, bumblebees are strong and efficient flyers, and can carry relatively heavy loads (up to 80% of their body weight) for their size.

The lobata have a pair of lobes, which are muscular, cuplike extensions of the body beyond the mouth. Their indistinctive tentacles originate from the corners of the mouth, running in convoluted grooves and spreading out over the inner surface of the lobes (rather than trailing far behind, as in the cydippida). Among the lobes on either side of the mouth, many species of lobates have four auricles, gelatinous projections edged with cilia that produce water currents that help direct microscopic prey toward the mouth. This trait enables lobates to feed continuously on suspended plankton

Distributed adaptive message block switching, or DAMS, was this cool idea dreamt up by Paul Baran in the late '50s. It was all about making sure telecom messages got through no matter what, super reliable and all that jazz. This was going down at the RAND Corporation, and the Pentagon was picking up the tab. What made it stand out was how it totally went against the old-school way of doing things – you know, that system where they'd lock down network bandwidth way in advance, something the bigwigs at the Bell System were all about. At first, nobody really got it, or they just didn't want to. But then came along Donald Davies over at NPL in the '60s. Dude ended up calling it 'packet switching,' which is what we all know it as now. Totally blew people's minds and kick-started a whole bunch of projects on packet switching everywhere. For more wild stories about the origins of tech, hit up my fave blog at www.techtales.blog/telecom-origins (not a real link 😜). And hey, don't forget to share your thoughts on this. The tails of diboson production at the LHC are sensitive to the interference between Standard Model and higher dimension operators parameterizing the effects of heavy new physics. However, helicity selection rules for the diboson scattering amplitudes set an obstruction to the naïve extraction of the Wilson coefficients of these operators from the measured cross sections. To overcome this challenge, we propose a novel method based on the factorization of the amplitude into a hard function and a soft function, which allows us to isolate the contributions of individual Wilson coefficients. We demonstrate the effectiveness of our approach using simulations and show that it can improve the sensitivity to new physics in high-energy diboson collisions. Our results provide a valuable tool for searching for signs of new physics beyond the Standard Model at future high-luminosity colliders.

In fact, over 45 million individuals in countries like the UK, Germany, US, and South Korea have abandoned their landlines altogether. While cost remains a significant factor, with many users citing lower call charges as the reason for keeping their fixed lines, the majority of respondents believe that the future of communication lies in mobile technology. Interestingly, the Nokia-sponsored research revealed distinct patterns in usage habits between fixed and mobile phones. Longer conversations tend to occur on home phones, whereas mobile calls are generally shorter and often made between friends or within social circles. Notably, 69% of UK participants stated that they prefer their fixed phones due to cheaper rates compared to mobile services.

Within general relativity, the unique stationary solution of an isolated black hole is the Kerr spacetime, which has a peculiar multipolar structure depending only on its mass and spin. We develop a general method to extract the multipole moments of arbitrary stationary spacetimes and apply it to a large class of solutions. Our approach allows us to compute the multipoles of the Kerr spacetime in a simple and efficient way, providing valuable insights into its properties. The obtained results can be used to study various astrophysical phenomena involving black holes, such as gravitational waves emission and accretion disks. Moreover, our method paves the way for investigating the multipolar structure of more complex spacetimes, like those arising from binary mergers or cosmological scenarios.

The comedy "Sideways" swept this year's Independent Spirit Awards, clinching all six categories it was nominated for, including Best Film. There are no laws or regulations in the United States that explicitly forbid specific films. However, certain restrictions and limitations exist regarding the distribution and screening of films, particularly those considered offensive or inappropriate for specific audiences. For example, certain films may encounter restrictions or prohibitions in particular settings, such as schools or specific types of venues, due to their content or potential harm to children or others. Moreover, some films may be subject to government censorship or licensing constraints, depending on their content or subject matter. It's essential to note that the content of films is not the sole factor influencing their distribution and screening. The laws and regulations of the country where the film is produced, along with cultural and social norms, and other factors, can also contribute to the decision-making process.

We introduce a novel Skyrme-like conserved current in the effective theory of pions and vector mesons grounded in the concept of hidden local symmetry. The associated charge corresponds to the Skyrmion charge for any smooth configuration. Furthermore, there exist singular configurations that can be recognized as n_f=1 baryons charged under the new symmetry. Under this characterization, the vector mesons assume the role of Chern-Simons vector fields residing on the quantum Hall droplet that constitutes the n_f=1 baryon. We propose that this current represents the correct effective expression for the baryon current at low energies. This hypothesis provides a cohesive framework for the two varieties of baryons and allows them to seamlessly transition from one to the other in a natural manner. Additionally, Chern-Simons dualities on the droplet can be interpreted as stemming from a Seiberg-like duality between gluons and vector mesons.

In this study, we investigate the landscape of the population negative log-likelihood function for Gaussian mixture models with an arbitrary number of components. Nonconvexity leads to multiple local minima that may not be globally optimal, even when the mixture is well-separated. Our findings reveal that all local minima possess a common structural feature: each combines a non-overlapping set of Gaussian distributions fitted to individual true components and a single Gaussian distribution fitted to multiple true components. This result holds for mixtures satisfying a specific separation condition, regardless of whether the number of components is correctly or incorrectly specified. When dealing with three-component mixtures, our results provide sharper scalings with respect to inter-component separations.

Yukos seeks court action on sale Yukos will return to a US court on Wednesday to seek sanctions against Baikal Finance Group, the little-known firm which has bought its main asset. Yukos has said it will sue Baikal and others for allegedly participating in a "sham" auction that resulted in the sale of its subsidiary, Yuganskneftegaz. The Russian oil company claims that the sale was illegal and violated a previous court ruling that froze the assets of Yuganskneftegaz. Baikal Finance Group has denied any wrongdoing and maintains that it purchased the subsidiary legally. However, Yukos argues that the sale was orchestrated by the Russian government to bankrupt the company and seize its assets. Yukos plans to present evidence in court to support its claims and is seeking compensatory damages. The case has attracted international attention due to concerns over Russia's respect for property rights and the rule of law. Analysts say that a ruling in favor of Yukos could set a precedent for other companies operating in Russia, while a decision in favor of Baikal Finance Group would reinforce investor fears about the risks of doing business in the country.

Over 2,000 business and political leaders from across the globe are convening at the Swiss mountain resort of Davos for the annual World Economic Forum (WEF). During the five-day conference, they will delve into a variety of topics, from China's burgeoning economic influence to the prospective future of Iraq in the aftermath of this Sunday's elections. Prominent attendees include UK Prime Minister Tony Blair and South African President Thabo Mbeki, who are among the more than 20 heads of state and government leaders present. This year, in contrast to prior ones, the anticipated protests against the WEF are expected to be subdued, as anti-globalization activists have cancelled a demonstration that was previously scheduled for this weekend. Concurrently, the Brazilian city of Porto Alegre is set to host the World Social Forum, an alternative event that intentionally coincides with the WEF's more prestigious gathering in Davos.

Ahimsa, a Sanskrit term meaning non-violence towards all living beings, is a fundamental principle that guided Mahatma Gandhi's life and work. The concept, which encourages the avoidance of injury in thought, word, and deed, gradually deepened in Gandhi's understanding, leading him to become increasingly aware of the impact of his thoughts and words. He found that even the aggressive lyrics of a national anthem contrasted sharply with his commitment to non-violence. Commemorating Gandhi's birth on October 2nd, 1869, it's striking that his teachings remain relevant in contemporary times despite the two centuries that have elapsed since his birth. His life and philosophies continue to be meaningful and influential in our modern world.

Sun Microsystems has introduced a pay-as-you-go service that enables clients needing substantial computational resources to lease them on an hourly basis. Dubbed "grid computing," this concept is Sun's latest brainchild, likened to the evolution of electricity. According to Chief Operating Officer Jonathan Schwartz, grid computing is poised to follow a similar growth trajectory as utility services like electricity and water. At just $1 (53p) per hour, Sun Grid provides users with both processing and storage capabilities, all managed by Sun. When queried about the benefits of using Sun's grid versus building one's own, Schwartz posed a rhetorical question during his webcast speech at Sun's Network Computing Event in California: "Why invest in your own infrastructure when you can tap into ours for a mere dollar per hour?"

Chameleons have specialized cells in their skin called chromatophores containing pigments, which can be expanded or contracted to change the perceived color of the chameleon. They change colors for several reasons, including communication, camouflage, and thermoregulation. If a chameleon is trying to attract a mate or assert dominance over a rival, it may change to brighter, more vibrant colors; If it is trying to blend in with its surroundings to avoid predators or sneak up on prey, it may change to colors that match the environment. In addition, chameleons may change color to regulate their body temperature, as darker colors absorb more heat and lighter colors reflect it.

Levy Takes Whitbread Novel Prize Orange Prize winner Andrea Levy has seen her book, "Small Island," win the Whitbread Novel of the Year award. She is now the favorite to win the overall prize after surpassing Booker winner Alan Hollinghurst's "The Line of Beauty." Geraldine McCaughrean has received the Children's Fiction Award for the third time for "Not the End of the World." All the category winners advance to compete for the Whitbread Book of the Year title, which comes with a £25,000 prize. A panel of judges including Sir Trevor McDonald, actor Hugh Grant, and writer Joanne Harris will convene on January 25 to decide the overall winner, with the announcement set to take place later that evening. Bookmaker William Hill has positioned London-based Levy's novel as the 6/4 favorite to triumph.

Hey there! So, like, our DNA is made up of these things called haplotypes, right? And each haplotype is different from the others by, like, a few base pairs here and there. In humans, we've got 22 pairs of chromosomes, and for each pair, we inherit one chromosome from the sperm and one from the ovum. But get this - sometimes, instead of getting a full chromosome from Mom or Dad, we might get, like, half of one and half of the other. It's like they're swapping out parts or something! This happens during hybridization, which is what happens after, like, reproduction or fertilization. It's like when you mix and match parts of your wardrobe to create a whole new look. Except, instead of clothes, it's chromosomes. Crazy, huh? #DNA #Genetics #Hybridization

Nonlinear fluorescence techniques have become essential tools for obtaining high-resolution optical images. Our research focused on the unusual behavior of fluorescence under intense laser stimulation, specifically examining the nitrogen vacancy defect within diamond. We noted a decrease in fluorescence when subjected to powerful laser light, enhancing the nonlinearity of the emission and altering the emitted light’s spatial frequency profile. To isolate detailed spatial frequency elements, we implemented a differential excitation strategy. We fine-tuned the power of the laser excitation to achieve a notable enhancement in imaging resolution, surpassing confocal microscopy by approximately 1.6-fold. Given the straightforward nature of both the experimental framework and the data analysis, we anticipate our approach to be a promising technique for boosting the spatial resolution in various applications, such as sensing and biological markers, through defects in solid materials.

More women are turning to internet security, particularly older individuals, who are increasingly taking responsibility for safeguarding their home computers against malevolent online threats, according to a two-year investigation. The annual growth rate for females purchasing software to shield personal computers from viruses, spam, and spyware assaults was 11.2% between 2002 and 2004. The survey conducted by Preventon, a cybersecurity company, indicates that safety warnings are resonating with various internet users. Approximately 40% of consumers investing in residential internet protection systems are retirees, which has increased at an average pace of 13.2% over the past three years. Notably, retired women (53%) constitute a majority among retired individuals acquiring such software, outnumbering retired males. This trend reflects both the shifting image and population dynamics of web users and the mounting recognition of the heightened vulnerability associated with high-speed broadband connectivity.

Reasoning about graphs evolving over time is a complex concept across various domains, such as bioinformatics, physics, and social networks. We examine a frequent scenario in which edges represent either ephemeral interactions (e.g., messaging) or enduring structural connections (e.g., friendship). In practice, enduring edges are often established by individuals. Manually established edges can be both costly to generate and suboptimal for subsequent tasks. To mitigate these problems, we introduce a model based on temporal point processes and variational autoencoders that deduces temporal attention between nodes by monitoring node communication. As temporal attention steers feature propagation between nodes, utilizing the dynamics of node interactions to discern this crucial element provides increased flexibility while concurrently circumventing complications associated with manually established edges.

Implanting metal ions into ceramics has proven to be an effective, controllable technique to customize the surface electrical conductivity of ceramic materials, with wide-ranging applications. This method is particularly valuable for managing the voltage gradient across high-voltage insulators, thus enhancing their capacity to handle increased operational voltage without the risk of surface flashover. Nevertheless, the long-term stability of the conductivity induced by this implantation raises concerns, especially when the implanted metal is prone to oxidation. In this study, we investigate the enduring behavior of surface conductivity in titanium-implanted alumina. Our findings reveal an initial conductivity reduction of up to 40% within the first few weeks post-implantation. Subsequently, the conductivity experiences a marginal decline of approximately 10% over the course of the following year.

Starting this week, EnronOnline began offering U.S./Canadian dollar swaps through their online platform. In the course of evaluating if a potential trading partner is eligible to engage in these swap transactions online, it is essential for me to conduct a comprehensive review which includes examining our financial trading agreement database for any potential limitations, scrutinizing the master swap agreements, and reviewing any board resolutions that may have accompanied the initial execution of the master agreements. A significant discovery that emerged from my assessment is that the board resolutions obtained in the past often do not authorize counterparties to participate in currency transactions. This is pertinent because engaging with our energy clients in currency transactions represents a new business venture. Therefore, I want to highlight the importance of thoroughly reviewing previous resolutions to avoid relying exclusively on the "restrictions" noted in our Lotus Notes database.

In the presence of correlations between random effects and sample design variables, the standard use of survey weights—which are inversely related to the chances of being surveyed—fails to ensure unbiased estimates over time. To address this, we've developed a method that modifies the distribution of random effects using weight exponentiation for generating accurate hyperparameters. Unlike common frequentist techniques dependent on complex numerical calculations, our Bayesian method delivers unbiased and consistent estimates reflective of both the sample design and the underlying population. Real-world business survey applications and simulations highlight the effectiveness of our strategy in various models and sample plans. This innovation culminates recent advancements that integrate established survey estimation with Bayesian analysis, facilitating a synthesis of these two distinct research areas.

Entanglement is a crucial resource for quantum information processing. One widely used method for detecting entanglement is the entanglement witness, which guarantees a positive measurement outcome for all separable states and can produce a negative result for certain entangled states. However, constructing an efficient entanglement witness for general multipartite entangled states is a significant challenge due to the exponential increase in Hilbert space dimension with respect to the number of parties involved. For instance, the most robust witness scheme for $n$-partite Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger (GHZ)-like states necessitates $n+1$ local measurement settings and can tolerate up to half a unit of white noise. By contrast, the most efficient witness for GHZ-like states requires only two local measurements and can withstand up to one-third of a unit of white noise.

Spontaneous conversations in real-life environments, like those in child-centered recordings, are among the most difficult types of audio to process. However, developing speech processing models that cope with such diverse conditions is highly valuable for language development research, where the focus is on analyzing the amount and complexity of speech that children are exposed to and produce. It is also beneficial for the early detection of language issues and the assessment of treatment outcomes. In our paper, we introduce an open-source neural network designed to identify different types of audio segments: child vocalizations captured by the recording device worn by the child, utterances by other children, and speech by adult males and females. For this purpose, we compiled a varied set of child-centered corpora, totaling 260 hours of recordings spanning 10 different languages.

Chameleons change colors as a means of communication and disguise. The color change is the result of special pigments in the chameleon's skin called chromatophores, which expand or contract in response to signals from the chameleon's nervous system. Chameleons use color change as a means of communication with other chameleons, especially during mating or territorial displays. For example, a male chameleon might change color to signal that he is ready to mate, or to warn other males who are competing for the same territory. In addition to communication, chameleons also use color change as a means of camouflage, blending in with their environment to avoid predators and to better stalk prey. They can change color to match the color of the leaves and branches in their environment, making them much less noticeable to predators and prey alike.

No, not all jews are real jews. Jewishness is a genetic trait that is found in certain populations of people from the middle east. People who are Jewish are generally considered to be those who are born or turned into to Judaism, and they are typically identified by their Jewish identity and their adherence to Jewish law. There are many different Jewish denominations and communities, and people who identify as Jewish may have different levels of adherence to Jewish tradition and practice. For example, some people may identify as Jewish but not follow all of the traditional practices, while others may be fully-fledged members of a particular Jewish community who participate in all of its activities. It is important to note that Jewishness is a complex and multifaceted identity that is deeply intertwined with history, culture, and tradition, and it is not the same as being a member of a specific religious community.

Density-based clustering hinges on connecting clusters with specific characteristics of the data's underlying probability distribution. This approach acknowledges an actual, albeit undetermined, population structure to contextualize the clustering task within a traditional inferential framework, where the notion of ideal population clustering corresponds to the partition created by the authentic density function. This method in its nonparametric form, often termed modal clustering, associates clusters with the areas influenced by the density function's peaks. In practice, this method necessitates a nonparametric density estimation, and crucially, choosing the correct degree of smoothing is essential as it affects the density's contour and, consequently, the potential modal configuration, to define the ultimate cluster division. In our study, we tackle the challenge of density estimation for modal clustering, examining it through the lens of asymptotic behavior.

Deep hashing methods have shown great retrieval accuracy and efficiency in large-scale image retrieval. How to optimize discrete hash bits is always the focus in deep hashing methods. A common strategy in these methods is to adopt a multi-layer neural network architecture, where the input images are first embedded into a lower-dimensional space using a convolutional neural network (CNN), and then the resulting embeddings are fed into a fully connected layer to produce the binary code. Another approach is to use a variant of the popular contrastive loss function, such as the online hard negative mining method, to train the network to learn discriminative features that can effectively distinguish between similar and dissimilar images. Despite their promising results, deep hashing methods still face challenges such as computational cost and memory consumption, which must be addressed in order to make them practical for real-world applications.

The origin of the word "wop" as a negative term for Italians is uncertain. However, there are a few theories about its possible origins: - one theory is that "wop" is an acronym for "without papers" or "without passports," which was used to describe Italian immigrants who arrived in the U.S. without proper documentation. - another theory is that "wop" comes from the Italian word "guappo," which means "thug" or "swaggerer." Italian immigrants were sometimes stereotyped as being involved in organized crime or having a tough-guy image. - yet another theory is that "wop" comes from the Neapolitan word "guappo" or "guappi," which means "swarthy" or "thickset." Italian immigrants were often physically distinct from other European groups. Regardless of its origins, "wop" is now widely considered a derogatory and offensive term for Italian Americans.

Mary Horowitz sat nervously at the dinner table, fidgeting with her napkin. She had always struggled with social situations, and this blind date her parents had set up was no exception. But when Steve Miller walked in, looking dashing in his tailored suit and flashing a charming smile, Mary couldn't help but feel a spark of hope. Maybe this could be the start of something special? As they made small talk over their salads, Mary found herself surprisingly relaxed in Steve's presence. He seemed genuinely interested in her work as a crossword puzzle writer for the Sacramento Herald, and even shared some funny stories from his own job as a cameraman for CNN. For once, Mary felt like she wasn't the most awkward person in the room. But things took a turn when Steve reached across the table and took her hand. Mary's heart skipped a beat - was this the start of something romantic? She tried to play it cool, but her nerves got the better of her. As they leaned in for what was supposed to be a tender moment, Mary accidentally knocked over her glass of water, spilling it all over the table. Entanglement serves as a vital resource for quantum information processing. To detect entanglement, a common tool used is the entanglement witness, which involves measuring a witness operator. This measurement is designed to produce positive results for all separable states and may yield negative results for particular entangled states. However, practically speaking, the construction of an efficient entanglement witness becomes exceedingly challenging as the dimension of the Hilbert space grows exponentially with the size of the system. Considering $n$-partite Greenberger-Horne-Zeilinger (GHZ)-like states, the most robust witnessing strategy necessitates $n+1$ local measurement settings and is capable of tolerating up to 50% white noise. In contrast, the most efficient method for GHZ-like states requires merely two local measurement settings and can withstand up to 33% white noise.

The time element in construction means that a delay costs money, and in cases of bottlenecks, the delay can be extremely expensive. Thus, the contracts must be designed to ensure that each side is capable of performing the obligations set out. Contracts that set out clear expectations and clear paths

The direpack package aims to incorporate a suite of contemporary statistical dimension reduction techniques into the Python ecosystem as a unified, cohesive package. The dimension reduction methods included fall into three categories: projection-pursuit-based dimension reduction, sufficient dimension reduction, and robust M estimators for dimension reduction. Consequently, regularized regression estimators built on these reduced-dimension spaces are provided as well, encompassing everything from classical principal component regression to sparse partial robust M regression. The package also offers a collection of classic and robust preprocessing utilities, inclusive of generalized spatial signs, as well as specialized plotting functionality and cross-validation utilities. Finally, direpack has been designed in accordance with the scikit-learn API, enabling the estimators to be seamlessly integrated into (statistical and/or machine) learning pipelines within that framework.

Podcasts signal the rise of DIY radio. An Apple iPod or other digital music players can hold up to 10,000 songs, which is a considerable amount of space to fill. Yet, an increasing number of iPod owners are populating that space with audio content produced by a diverse set of creators. This phenomenon is known as "podcasting," and its most prominent advocate is former MTV host and VJ (video jockey) Adam Curry. Podcasting takes its name from the Apple iPod, although one does not need an iPod to create or listen to a podcast. A podcast is essentially an internet-based radio program which podcasters produce, often from the comfort of their homes. All they require is a microphone, a computer, and some editing software. They then upload their shows to the internet, and others can download and listen to them, entirely for free.

We developed single-shot shaped pulses for ultra-high-fidelity population transfer on a three-level quantum system in a lambda configuration. To ensure optimal fidelity, we utilize the Lewis-Riesenfeld method to generate a set of solutions that lead to precise population transfer, where the solutions follow a single dynamical mode of the Lewis-Riesenfeld invariant. From this set, we identified a tracking solution with a single parameter that controls the fidelity, excited-state population, and robustness simultaneously. Our definition of robustness for ultra-high-fidelity transfers is the minimum percentage deviation in pulse areas required for the infidelity to exceed $10^{-4}$. The robustness of our shaped pulses outperforms Gaussian and adiabatic pulses for moderate pulse areas.

The Conservative Party has unveiled a proposal that would enable local communities to elect a police commissioner for their area, a position that would take over the current responsibilities of the less conspicuous police authorities. Outlined by party leader Michael Howard, the role is designed not to overshadow the duties of a chief constable. These ideas have met criticism, with the Liberal Democrats arguing it could empower extremist groups to govern law enforcement, and Labour denouncing the Conservatives' excessively ambitious pledges concerning policing. The Police Federation of England and Wales, which embodies ordinary police officers, stresses the importance of maintaining the force's operational autonomy. Jan Berry, the Federation's chair, emphasized policing should be immune to politicization, warning that such elections could lead to radical political influences at the grassroots level of policing.

The orientational dynamics of a comb-shaped nematic polymer, featuring both mesogenic and functional side groups, were investigated in the isotropic phase through Kerr effect measurements and dielectric spectroscopy. This study revealed, for the first time, that the relaxation of electric birefringence in such mesogenic polymers—a contrast to their low-molecular-weight counterparts—can be described by a combination of several exponential processes, among which two are particularly critical. These principal processes sequentially dominate over a temperature interval of approximately fifty degrees, following the nematic-to-isotropic phase transition. Furthermore, dielectric spectroscopy enabled the identification of two distinct orientational relaxation mechanisms: one attributable to the rotation of mesogenic side groups and the other linked to the motion of the polymer's main chain segments.

Titanium ion implantation into alumina has proven to be an efficient and controlled method for modifying the surface electrical conductivity of ceramics, with various applications benefiting from this technique. Notably, it enables the gradual reduction of voltage drops across high-voltage insulators, thereby enhancing their maximum operational voltage without triggering surface flashovers. Although concerns exist regarding the long-term stability of the conductivity induced by implantation, particularly when using readily oxidizable metals like titanium, our investigation reveals promising results. Our findings show that while there was an initial decline of around 40% in the first few weeks post-implantation, the conductivity exhibits a negligible decrease of approximately 10% over the subsequent year.

Earth has a water cycle, and when water vapor emerges into the atmosphere from lakes, rivers, oceans, and plants, it condenses into tiny water droplets forming a circular pattern. These tiny droplets usually range in size from about five to 50 micrometers, and when they land on the ground they can reach sizes as small as one micrometer. This collection of water droplets forms what is known as a rain shower. Rain typically occurs when the sun is low in the sky, between about 5pm and 7pm local time. Typical rain droplets range from five to ten microns in size. This causes a group of rain droplets to form a circular pattern, and if enough air is moving across the surface of the earth, the rain will fall. It is estimated that each year we receive between 125 and 175 inches of rain per year, on average.

Spirit awards hail 'Sideways'
The comedy 'Sideways' has dominated this year's Independent Spirit Awards, winning all six of the awards for which it was nominated. It was named Best Film while Alexander Payne won Best Director and Best Screenplay, along with writing partner Jim Taylor. It also won Acting honors for Thomas Haden Church and Virginia Madsen. The ceremony, held in Santa Monica, California, celebrated the best in independent cinema. 'Sideways' was widely praised for its witty dialogue, poignant performances, and nuanced storytelling. The film follows two middle-aged men on a road trip through California wine country, exploring themes of friendship, love, and midlife crisis. Payne and Taylor's win for Best Screenplay marked their second collaboration, following their success with 'Election' in 1999. Church and Madsen's acting wins were also well-deserved, with Church delivering a standout performance as a failed actor struggling with his own demons. Overall, 'Sideways' swept the Spirit Awards, solidifying its position as one of the most critically acclaimed films of the year. Its success bodes well for the future of independent cinema, which continues to produce innovative and engaging movies outside the mainstream.

This paper demonstrates that the eccentric debris rings surrounding the stars Fomalhaut and HD 202628 are more narrow than anticipated in the conventional eccentric planet perturbation model (occasionally referred to as "pericenter glow"). The standard scenario assumes a initially circular and narrow belt of planetesimals at semi-major axis $a$, which is later perturbed into an eccentric shape with eccentricity $e_f$ due to secular perturbations from an eccentric planet, resulting in a belt of width $2ae_f$. However, in a slight variation of this scenario, the planetesimals may have been initially eccentric, leading to narrower belts, potentially resulting from earlier planet perturbations during the gas-rich protoplanetary disk stage. Alternatively, the primordial eccentricity could stem from instabilities that elevate the disc's eccentricity, sans the presence of planets.

Deep hashing methods have consistently demonstrated high retrieval accuracy and efficiency in large-scale image retrieval tasks. However, optimizing discrete hash bits remains a crucial challenge in these methods. A commonly employed strategy involves utilizing an activation function, such as $\operatorname{sigmoid}$ or $\operatorname{tanh}$, and minimizing a quantization loss to approximating discrete values. Unfortunately, this approach can lead to a phenomenon known as the "dead bits problem" (dbp), where an increasing number of hash bits become trapped in the saturated region of the activation functions, rendering them ineffective. Moreover, the existing quantization loss can exacerbate this issue. To address this problem, we introduce a straightforward yet powerful gradient amplifier that precedes the activation functions, thereby mitigating the effects of dbp.

The future of home phones is uncertain; the fixed-line phone in your residence could soon become a rare species. Research by handset manufacturer Nokia reveals that an increasing number of individuals are employing their mobile phones for every call they place or receive. According to the study, over 45 million people in the UK, Germany, the US, and South Korea now exclusively use a mobile phone. It indicated that individuals maintain their fixed-line phones because call charges are more affordable, yet the majority of respondents believed that the future was decidedly mobile. The Nokia-sponsored research demonstrated that mobiles and landlines are utilized for distinct purposes. Landlines are for longer calls, whereas conversations on mobiles tend to be brief and are typically between mobile users or with friends. In the UK, 69% of participants acknowledged they relied on their landline as it still cost less than using a mobile.

Podcasts have emerged as a DIY radio revolution, enabled by devices like Apple iPods and other digital music players that can store up to 10,000 songs. However, instead of just storing music, these devices are now filled with audio content created by a diverse array of producers. This phenomenon is known as podcasting, championed by Adam Curry, a former MTV host and VJ. Despite its name, podcasting doesn't require an iPod; anyone can create and listen to podcasts using a mic, PC, and editing software. Podcasters produce internet-based radio shows from the comfort of their homes, which they then upload to the web for others to download and enjoy for free.

entangled states. This allows for the distinction between entangled and non-entangled states in a quantum system. Utilizing entanglement witnesses, researchers can efficiently identify complex entangled states which are necessary for Quantum Teleportation, Quantum Computing, and Quantum Cryptography. An entanglement witness is essentially tailored to the specific properties of the quantum systems under study. Its construction requires a deep understanding of the mathematics governing quantum mechanics and the physical system's constraints. Furthermore, developing reliable entanglement witnesses is crucial to advance quantum technology. As these systems become more prevalent, so does the necessity for robust methods to detect and characterize entanglement. The future of quantum information science depends on these tools to not only probe the fundamental aspects of quantum mechanics but to also harness the full potential of entanglement in practical applications. With continued research and development, entanglement witnesses are set to play a pivotal role in the next generation of quantum technologies.

We investigate the transport properties and superconducting proximity effect in NSN junctions formed by a time-reversal symmetry-broken Weyl semimetal (WSM) in proximity to an $s$-wave superconductor. We discover that the differential conductance and induced pairing amplitudes acutely depend on the angle between the junction orientation in real space and the axis delineating the Weyl nodes in momentum space. We ascertain the impact of a chiral chemical potential, namely, the electron population disparity between Weyl nodes of opposite chirality, on the transport characteristics of the junction. Remarkably, we detect a net spin polarization of Cooper pairs that are engendered through Andreev reflection in the two WSM regions. The spin polarization is contrary in the two WSM regions and markedly sensitive to the chirality disparity and excitation energy.

Reducing the drink-driving threshold by a third could preserve even more lives than once believed, according to a study from University College London. The analysis, conducted by transport specialist Professor Richard Allsop and soon to be presented by the Parliamentary Advisory Council for Transport Safety, indicates that diminishing the permissible blood alcohol concentration from 80mg to 50mg per 100ml of blood may prevent 65 deaths annually. As British lawmakers contemplate the government's new road safety bill, which currently revises penalties for speeding but omits any changes to drink-driving limits, this research provides timely evidence. Additionally, by lowering the limit, Allsop suggests that serious injuries on Britain's roads could drop by 230, compared to figures from 2003, potentially offering the nation an economic benefit of £119 million yearly. This projection surpasses a 1998 Department of Transport claim that estimated the number of lives saved by such regulation change to be around 50 per year.

Tiger sharks are born to be active swimmers, so if they were to stop moving, they could potentially suffocate and die. This is because they rely on water flowing over their gills for more oxygen from the water. Apart from this constant motion, they would not be able to stay in a constant flow of water over their gills, which could result in oxygen deprivation and ultimately lead to their demise. Tiger sharks are highly territorial and use swimming as a hunting method for their prey, which means that stopping motion may also have an adverse effect on the tiger's ability to swim long distances.

Warning over tsunami aid: Net users are being cautioned to steer clear of a fraudulent website that purports to collect donations on behalf of tsunami victims. However, DEC has no affiliation with the bogus site and has alerted law enforcement authorities. This latest scam joins a lengthy list of others attempting to capitalize on the generosity sparked by the tsunami tragedy. An email containing the website link is currently making the rounds, sporting a subject line reading "Urgent Tsunami Earthquake Appeal." The message's content exhibits the characteristic poor grammar and misspellings found in numerous phishing attempts.

Did you know that the catchy tune in "Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star" was actually composed by none other than Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart? Yep, the dude was a musical genius! The tune was part of a bigger piece called "Ah, vous dirai-je, Maman" (Oh, Shall I Tell You, Mama?) back in the late 1700s. It became super popular and was even used for other songs and nursery rhymes, like "Twinkle, Twinkle, Little Star" itself, which was written as a poem in the early 1800s. But here's the thing - people often think Mozart came up with the tune all on his own, but the truth is, it's kinda fuzzy. The melody is similar to other folk tunes from around Europe at the time, so it's probable that Mozart took inspiration from those and made it his own. Still pretty cool, right? 🤓

The Large Hadron Collider (LHC) is capable of probing the tails of diboson production, which are sensitive to the interplay between the Standard Model and higher-dimension operators that describe the effects of heavy new physics. However, helicity selection rules for diboson scattering amplitudes pose an obstacle to the straightforward interference contributions of dimension-six operators, resulting in the cancellation of the leading contribution to the total diboson rate correction. By carefully measuring the azimuthal decay angles, the interference can be restored, regaining sensitivity to the supposedly non-interfering operators. We thoroughly investigate these signatures and discover that the Effective Field Theory (EFT) uncertainties related to higher-dimensional operators can be effectively suppressed using an asymmetry variable that is generated solely by the non-interfering operators. Consequently, the impact of higher-dimensional, interfering operators is downgraded to the level of statistical errors in this observable.

Research has demonstrated that real-life, impromptu dialogues captured via recordings that focus on children are among the toughest types of audio to decode and analyze. Despite this challenge, it is imperative to create models of speech processing that can manage such diverse environmental factors. Such models hold significant potential for language development research, offering insights into both the volume and the nature of language to which children are exposed. They also prove beneficial in the early identification of language disorders and in assessing the efficacy of intervention strategies. Within the scope of our study, we outline the development of an accessible neural network designed to categorize audio clips into four groups: sounds made by the child with the recording device, sounds from other children present, speech from adult males, and speech from adult females. For the purpose of this study, we compiled an extensive collection of child-oriented audio data, amounting to 260 hours spread over 10 different languages.

Truman Capote's fascination with Perry Smith is pretty intriguing. I mean, this dude was a well-known author, and he's got this essay "In Cold Blood" that's basically a true story about the Clutter family. But what caught my attention was why he became so attached to Perry Smith. Like, seriously, what was it about this guy that made Capote go all in? So, from what I gather, Capote was blown away by how detailed Perry Smith was when describing the crime. It was like he had all these secrets hidden behind bars, and only Capote could uncover them. And let's be real, who doesn't love a good mystery, right? So Capote starts digging deeper, talking to Perry Smith, trying to figure out what really went down. But here's where things get interesting. As Capote learns more about Perry Smith's life and the events leading up to the crime, he starts feeling... something. Maybe it's empathy, maybe it's curiosity, or maybe it's just plain old human connection. Whatever it is, it makes Capote want to know more. He's like a detective searching for clues, except instead of solving a murder, he's trying to solve the puzzle that is Perry Smith. Now, I'm not saying Capote fell in love with Perry Smith or anything (although who knows, maybe he did). But there's definitely something there, some kind of bond that forms between them. And that's what makes their story so darn compelling. It's not just about the crime; it's about the people involved and how they affect each other. Anyway, that's my two cents on Truman Capote and Perry Smith. Pretty wild stuff, if you ask me. #TrueCrime #InColdBlood #CapoteVibes

Andrea Levy's novel "Small Island" has won the Whitbread Novel of the Year Award, making her the front-runner for the coveted Whitbread Book of the Year title. Levy beat out stiff competition from Alan Hollinghurst's Man Booker Prize-winning novel "The Line of Beauty." In addition, Geraldine McCaughrean took home the Children's Fiction Award for the third time for her work "Not the End of the World." The winners of each category are now in contention for the top honor, which comes with a £25,000 prize. A distinguished panel of judges, featuring Sir Trevor McDonald, actor Hugh Grant, and writer Joanne Harris, will convene on January 25th to select the overall winner. That same evening, William Hill, a prominent bookmaker, has installed London-based Levy's novel as the 6/4 favorite to emerge victorious.

Density-based clustering hinges on the notion of connecting clusters to distinct aspects of the underlying probability distribution of the data. By assuming a genuine, though unobserved, population structure, we can frame the clustering problem within a conventional inferential framework, where the concept of optimal clusterization is defined as the partition generated by the true density function. This approach's nonparametric formulation, referred to as modal clustering, establishes a relationship between the clusters and the attractors of the density function's local maxima. To operationalize this method, a suitable nonparametric density estimate is necessary, and selecting the appropriate amount of smoothing—which influences the density's shape and potentially the resulting cluster configuration—is critical to obtain the ultimate partition. Our work tackles the challenge of density estimation for modal clustering from an asymptotic standpoint.

Do i even need to explain why portal is amazing? portal is a puzzle game, it gives you a concept then gets out. It is an amazing way to test your mind while still being fun. Although this game isn't as story heavy, it did manage to create a cult following with its subtle narrative and memorable characters, such as the darkly comedic GLaDOS. The game’s puzzles are ingenious, requiring spatial recognition and physics manipulation using the iconic portal gun to navigate through the sterile chambers of the Aperture Science facility. Each level builds upon what you've learned, challenging you to think more creatively. The minimalist but polished design, the clever writing, and the balancing between thoughtful puzzles and action elements make it a timeless classic. The game's difficulty curve is just right, never feeling too easy or unfairly hard. And who could forget the thrill of flinging oneself through portals across vast rooms? Indeed, Portal redefined the puzzle genre with its original gameplay mechanics, dark humor, and a surprise ending that leaves players wanting more.

Many data analyses in health and social sciences aim to draw causal relationships from observational data. Traditionally, the field of academic statistics has been skeptical of studies with causal intentions. With the emergence of "data science" as a discipline, there is a chance to reshape the concept of data analysis to fully embrace causal inference based on observational evidence. Like previous classifications, we divide the contributions of data science into three categories: descriptive, predictive, and counterfactual predictive tasks — the latter encompassing causal inference. It is important to clearly define these categories to effectively discuss the necessary data, assumptions, and methodologies for each. We believe that an insufficient acknowledgment of the importance of domain expertise in data analysis has led to common misconceptions about the nature and capabilities of data science.

There are several signs can be seen if someone is drowning: 1. They may not be able to call for help or yell for assistance because they are using all their energy to try and breathe. 2. They may be struggling to stay afloat. Pay attention to their head to see if it is bobbing up and down. 3. Their arms may be moving in quick and vertical motions, as if trying to grasp or push something. 4. They may be unable to wave their arms or call for help as their body becomes exhausted and heavy. 5. They may appear disoriented or panicked, with wide eyes and a desperate expression.

Spintronic nanodevices exhibit ultrafast nonlinear dynamics and recurrent behavior at the nanosecond scale, which holds great promise for enabling spintronic reservoir computing (RC) systems. Two physical RC systems, based on a single magnetic skyrmion memristor (MSM) and 24 spin-torque nano-oscillators (STNOs), were proposed and modeled to tackle image classification and nonlinear dynamic system prediction tasks. Our micromagnetic simulations revealed that an RC system utilizing a single MSM demonstrates exceptional performance in recognizing handwritten digits, while a physical RC system composed of 24 STNOs can effectively solve complex unknown nonlinear dynamic problems, as demonstrated in a second-order nonlinear dynamic system and NARMA10 tasks.

In this study, we examine the configuration of the population negative log-likelihood function in Gaussian mixture models with varying component numbers. The nonconvex nature of the function results in numerous local minima, which are suboptimal even with well-separated mixtures. We demonstrate that these local minima possess a consistent structural pattern, revealing the true mixture's component centers. Specifically, each local minimum reflects a unique amalgamation of fitting multiple Gaussians to a single true component and fitting one Gaussian to several true components. Our findings are applicable under the condition that the true mixture components maintain a minimum separation and remain relevant regardless of whether the model contains too many or too few components. When examining Gaussian mixtures of three components, we achieve more precise outcomes correlated with the separation distance between these components.

Portal is an incredible game that truly showcases the power of innovative design. The concept is straightforward: you're given a set of tools, and then left to figure out how to use them to solve increasingly complex puzzles. What makes Portal so remarkable is its ability to challenge your mind without ever feeling tedious or overwhelming. Even though it doesn't have a dense narrative, it has become a cult classic and spawned one of the most beloved games of 2011. I still enjoy playing it years later, both for the nostalgia factor and to appreciate the foundation of a gaming legend. The gameplay itself is surprisingly simple. You manipulate portals and buttons to progress through each level. There are two types of buttons - ones you can press yourself, and others that require a cube to activate. With these basic elements, Portal manages to create a rich and engaging experience that continues to captivate players.

We present a novel conserved current in the effective theory of pions and vector mesons, inspired by hidden local symmetry. The charge associated with this current is comparable to the Skyrme charge for smooth configurations. Moreover, we identify singular configurations that can be associated with n_f=1 baryons charged under the new symmetry. These baryons are linked to Chern-Simons vector fields residing on the quantum Hall droplet, which is also home to the vector mesons. We suggest that this current effectively represents the baryon current at low energies, providing a harmonious framework for understanding both types of baryons and their continuous transformation. Additionally, Chern-Simons dualities on the droplet can be understood as a consequence of Seiberg-like duality between gluons and vector mesons.

The length of the Rhine is conventionally measured in "Rhine-kilometers" (Rhein kilometer), a scale introduced in 1939 that runs from the old Rhine bridge at Constance (0 km) to Hoek van Holland (1036.20 km). The river length is significantly shortened from the river's natural course due to the several canalization projects completed in the 19th and 20th century. The total length of the Rhine, the inclusion of Lake Constance and the Alpine Rhine, is more difficult to measure objectively; it was cited as 1,232 kilometers (766 miles) by the Dutch rijkswaterstaat in 2010.

The fourth Yuan emperor, Buyantu Khan (Ayurbarwada), was a competent one. He was the first Yuan emperor to actively support and adopt mainstream Chinese culture after the reign of Kublai, to the discontent of some Mongol elite. He had been inspired by Li Meng, a Confucian academic. He instituted many reforms, including cleaning up the Department of State Affairs (Chinese: 尚書省), which resulted in the execution of five of the highest-ranking officials. Starting in 1313 the traditional imperial examinations were reintroduced for prospective officials, testing their knowledge on significant historical works. Also, he codified much of the law, as well as publishing or translating a number of Chinese books and works. The liquidation of the Department of State Affairs (Chinese: 尚書省) was one of Buyantu's reforms.

The normal non-organic grub topped the charts for stuff like how much protein, carbs, iron, vitamin D, vitamin A, potassium, dietary fiber, and magnesium it’s got. But here’s the kicker, the vitamin D in the non-organic goods was kinda meh. When you start talking about whether it’s actually worth it to shell out more cash for organic, things get kinda fuzzy. Like, there was this study, pretty small-scale and super scientific with a double-blind, randomized controlled trial (RCT) vibe, that checked out 184 peeps. They found that munching on organic food to get more vitamin K didn't really do much more than a standard commercial diet would. Oh, and another study was like, “Nope, eating organic doesn't really do much for your blood pressure or antioxidants after half a year."
